4.2.0.7 Exercise

To be very honest, the Memphis-fan of the previous exercise actually was not very careful about keeping track of the number of cards he collected. He really only knows for sure that he collected between 20 and 24 cards before his first Memphis.

  1. Write down the log likelihood (pen and paper), and plot it.
  2. Maximize the loglikelihood and find the MLE of the probability of finding a Memphis.
Click for the answer
  1. The likelihood is \[ {\rm likelihood}(p) = (1-p)^{20}p + (1-p)^{21}p + (1-p)^{22}p + (1-p)^{23}p + (1-p)^{24}p\] The log likelihood is just the log of the likelihood. There is no nice expression, though. To plot the log likelihood
p=seq(0.01,1,0.001)
lik=dgeom(20,p) + dgeom(21,p) + dgeom(22,p) + dgeom(23,p) + dgeom(24,p)
plot(p,log(lik),type="l")

# and maximize:
loglik = function(p){
 log(sum(dgeom(20:24,p)))
}
optimize(loglik,c(0,1),maximum=TRUE)  # mle = 0.0436
## $maximum
## [1] 0.04364423
## 
## $objective
## [1] -2.502012

\(~\)

This last exercise demonstrates why the method of maximum likelihood is much more versatile than the method of moments. Indeed, there is no obvious way to apply the method of moments to this type of incomplete or “censored” data.

\(~\)

Now let us do a continuous distribution. The likelihood is simply the product of the densities at the data points. Again, we prefer to work with the logarithm of the likelihood.

4.2.0.8 Exercise

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find (in grams) \(X_1=983,\ X_2=1041,\ X_3=1026,\ X_4=1025,\ X_5=1033,\ X_6=968,\ X_7=1028\). Suppose we know that the (population) standard deviation of the weights is 25 grams.

  1. Which probability distribution is appropriate to model these data?
  2. Compute is the method of moments estimate of the (population) average weight.
  3. Write down the log likelihood (pen and paper), and plot it.
  4. Maximize the loglikelihood and and find the MLE of the (population) average weight.
Click for the answer

The “appropriate” distribution is the normal distribution. The likelihood is:” \[ {\rm likelihood}(\mu) = \prod_{i=1}^{7} \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{-(x(i) - \mu)^2/2\sigma^2}\] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^{7} [ -\log(\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}) - (x(i)-\mu)^2/2\sigma^2 ]\]

  1. The method of moments estimate of the expectation is just the average.
x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)
mean(x)
## [1] 1014.857
  1. Compute the MLE:
mu=seq(950,1050,1)     # "guessing" the MLE is somewhere between 950 and 1050
loglik=0
for (i in 1:7){
  loglik = loglik + log(dnorm(x[i],mu,25))
}
plot(mu,loglik,type='l')

# use grid search
ind=which.max(loglik)
mu[ind]        # mle of mu         
## [1] 1015
# or, using optimize,
ll = function(mu){
 sum(log(dnorm(x,mu,25)))
}
optimize(ll,c(0,2000),maximum=TRUE)  # mle of mu
## $maximum
## [1] 1014.857
## 
## $objective
## [1] -32.66299

4.2.0.9 Exercise

A manufacturer tests 10 light bulbs and records how many months they burn continuously before burning out. She finds 8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9 and 3.1 months.

  1. Which probability distribution is appropriate to model these data?

Click for the answer
  1. The “appropriate” distribution is the Exponential distribution. The Exponential distribution is parametrized by the “rate” lambda, which is 1/expectation. The likelihood is: \[ {\rm likelihood}(\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^{10} \lambda e^{-\lambda x(i)}\] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^{10} [ \log(\lambda) - \lambda x(i) ]\]
  2. The method of moments estimate of the expectation is just the average.
x=c(8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9, 3.1)

## [1] 10.81

expectation=seq(5,20,0.1)     # "guessing" the MLE is somewhere between 5 and 20
lambda=1/expectation
loglik=0
for (i in 1:10){
  loglik = loglik + log(dexp(x[i],lambda))
}
plot(lambda,loglik,type='l')

# use grid search
ind=which.max(loglik)
lambda[ind]        # mle of lambda         
## [1] 0.09259259
1/lambda[ind]      # mle of 1/lambda (same as expectation[ind])
## [1] 10.8

 sum(log(dexp(x,lambda)))
}

4.2.0.10 Exercise

A manufacturer tests 11 light bulbs and records how many months they burn continuously before burning out. She finds 8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9 and 3.1 months. The eleventh bulb is still burning at 24 months when the experiment ends.

  1. Write down the log likelihood (pen and paper), and plot it.
  2. Maximize the loglikelihood and and find the MLE of the expected number of burning months.
Click for the answer
  1. The cumulative distribution function of the exponential distribution is \[F(x) = 1 - exp(-\lambda x)$. So $P(X>24) = exp(-\lambda 24).\] The likelihood now becomes: \[ {\rm likelihood}(\lambda) = e^{-\lambda x(11)} \prod_{i=1}^{10} \lambda e^{-\lambda x(i)}\] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\lambda) = -\lambda x(11) + \sum_{i=1}^{10} [ \log(\lambda) - \lambda x(i) ]\]

The appropriate distribution is the Exponential. R parametrizes the exponential distribution by its “rate” which is 1/expectation.

x=c(8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9, 3.1, 24)  # add X_11

expectation=seq(5,20,0.1)     # "guessing" the MLE is somewhere between 5 and 20
lambda=1/expectation
loglik=0
for (i in 1:10){
  loglik = loglik + log(dexp(x[i],lambda))
}
loglik = loglik + log(1 - pexp(x[11],lambda)) # the prob of lasting longer than 24.
plot(lambda,loglik,type='l')

# use grid search
ind=which.max(loglik)
lambda[ind]        # mle of lambda         
## [1] 0.07575758
1/lambda[ind]      # mle of 1/lambda (same as expectation[ind])
## [1] 13.2
# or, using optimize,
ll = function(lambda){
 sum(log(dexp(x[1:10],lambda)))  + log(1 - pexp(x[11],lambda))
}
optimize(ll,c(0,1),maximum=TRUE) # mle of lambda
## $maximum
## [1] 0.07568509

1/0.07568509                     # mle of 1/lambda

theta=10
x=seq(-60,60,0.01)
plot(x,exp(-abs(x)/theta)/(2*theta),type="l",ylab="density")

and the log likelihood is \[{\rm loglikelihood}(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{10} -\log(2\theta) - |x_i|/\theta\]

4.2.0.12 Exercise

The capture-recapture method was used to estimate the size of an animal population. First, 100 animals are captured and tagged. Some time later, another 50 animals are captured, and it is found that 20 of them are tagged.

  1. Write down the likelihood. Hint: consider the so-called hypergeometric distribution.
  2. Use the R function dhyper to plot the likelihood.
  3. Compute the MLE of the population size.
Click for the answer
  1. If the size of the population is \(N\), then the probability of the observation is \(\frac{{100 \choose 20}{N-100 \choose 30}}{{N \choose 50}}\).

b/c.

N=100:1000         # guess the population is somewhere between 100 and 1000
lik=dhyper(20,100,N-100,50)
plot(N,lik)

N[which.max(lik)]  # MLE
## [1] 249

In this case, optimize is not a very good choice, because the inputs of dhyper must be integers. However, we can fix this problem by rounding:

lik.fun = function(N){
  N=round(N)
  dhyper(20,100,N-100,50)
}
optimize(lik.fun,interval=c(0,1000),maximum=TRUE)
## $maximum
## [1] 249.2378
## 
## $objective
## [1] 0.1280466

\(~\)

We end this section with an example where we estimate two parameters simultaneously. This will not be part of the exam!

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find (in grams) \(X_1=983,\ X_2=1041,\ X_3=1026,\ X_4=1025,\ X_5=1033,\ X_6=968,\ X_7=1028\). Suppose we do not know the standard deviation of the weights.

If we are willing to assume that these weights follow the normal probability distribution, we can apply the method of maximum likelihood to estimate the two parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\).

\(~\)

4.2.0.13 Exercise

Are you “willing to assume the weights follow a normal distribution”?

Click for the answer The trouble is that there is really no way to tell based on a sample of just 7 bags. However, there are no obvious outliers that could throw everything off, so it is pretty safe to assume normality.

\(~\)

Here is some very inefficient code to compute the MLE. It works by trying out many combinations of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) and always keeping the ones that increase the log likelihood. In the end we are left with the pair that maximizes the likelihood.

x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)
loglik=-Inf
for (m in seq(900,1100,0.1)){
  for (s in seq(10,40,0.1)){
     tmp=sum(log(dnorm(x,m,s)))  # compute the loglikelihood by summing
     if (tmp>loglik){
        loglik=tmp
        mu=m
        sigma=s
     }
  }
}
mu
## [1] 1014.9
sigma
## [1] 25.7

4.2.0.14 Exercise

Read the code, make sure you understand it, and run it. What is bad or inefficient about it?
Click for the answer We have to start by choosing some reasonable values for mu and sigma, and that is not so easy. And even then, we still spend a lot of time evaluating the log likelihood at parameter values that are nowhere near the optimum.

\(~\)

To find the MLE, it’s much better to use an optimizer. Until now we have used optimize but that can only optimize functions of a single parameter. To handle two parameters, we can use optim.

x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)
ll = function(theta,x) {         # We define an R function that computes the log likelihood
   mu=theta[1]
   sigma=theta[2]
   -sum(log(dnorm(x,mu,sigma)))  # compute loglikelihood by summing
}                                # add a minus sign, because optim *minimizes*.
optim(c(1000,25),ll,x=x,method="BFGS")
## $par
## [1] 1014.86313   25.69854
## 
## $value
## [1] 32.65757
## 
## $counts
## function gradient 
##       21       18 
## 
## $convergence
## [1] 0
## 
## $message
## NULL

4.2.0.15 Exercise

Run the code.
Click for the answer Fast, isn’t it?

4.3 What have we learned

  • We know the method of maximum likelihood
  • We can write down the likelihood (and log likelihood) in some standard situations
  • We can compute the maximum likelihood estimator
    • by grid search
    • by using optimize

\(~\)

5 The score function

We now know how to write down the likelihood for our data and use it to find the maximum likelihood estimator. The likelihood has many more uses than just for finding the maximum likelihood estimator, however! Today, we’ll explore the concept of likelihood in more depth. Throughout, we will focus on the log likelihood.

We will see that the log likelihood is much a more useful and fundamental concept than the likelihood itself. You will often notice that statisticians, when speaking about the likelihood, actually mean the log likelihood.

5.1 Computing the MLE exactly

If the log likelihood is not too complicated, then we can use mathematics to find the maximum. The basic idea is to take the derivative of the log likelihood and set it equal to zero. For example, consider the binomial model. If we have \(x\) successes out of \(n\) tries, then the likelihood is \[{\rm lik}(p) = {n \choose x} p^x (1-p)^{n-x},\]

and the log likelihood is \[{\rm loglik}(p) = \log {n \choose x} + x \log(p) + (n-x) \log(1-p).\] Taking the derivative with respect to \(p\) (remember the chain rule!) and bringing to a common denominator, we get \[{\rm loglik}'(p) = \frac{x}{p} - \frac{n-x}{1-p} = \frac{x - np}{p(1-p)}.\] Now we set this equal to zero and solve for \(p\). That means solving \(x-np=0\), so we find \(\hat p=x/n\). That’s the MLE exactly.

\(~\)

5.1.0.1 Excercise

Suppose that X is a discrete random variable with \(P(X=0)=\frac{2}{3}\theta\), \(P(X=1)=\frac13 \theta\), \(P(X=2)=\frac23 (1-\theta)\) and \(P(X=3)=\frac13(1-\theta)\). The following 10 independent observations were taken from such a distribution: (3, 0, 2, 1, 3, 2, 1, 0, 2, 1). Maximize the loglikelihood and find the MLE.

Click for the answer

The likelihood is

\[\text{lik}(\theta) = \left(\frac23 \theta\right)^2 \left(\frac13 \theta\right)^3\left(\frac23 (1-\theta)\right)^3 \left( \frac13(1-\theta) \right)^2 \]

The log likelihood is \[\text{loglik}(\theta) = 2 \log(\frac23 \theta) + 3 \log(\frac13 \theta) + 3 \log(\frac23(1-\theta)) + 2 \log(\frac13(1-\theta)) \]

Taking the derivative, we get \[\text{loglik}'(\theta) = \frac2\theta + \frac3\theta - \frac3{(1-\theta)} - \frac2{(1-\theta)} = \frac5\theta - \frac5{(1-\theta)}\]

Setting this derivative to zero, we get \[\frac5\theta = \frac5{(1-\theta)}.\] Equivalently, \(\theta = (1-\theta)\), so \(2 \theta =1\), so \(\theta = 1/2.\)

\(~\)

5.1.0.2 Exercise

If gene frequencies are in equilibrium, the genotypes AA, Aa, and aa occur in a population with frequencies \((1 − \theta)^2\), \(2\theta(1 − \theta)\), and \(\theta^2\), according to the Hardy- Weinberg law. Suppose that in a particular population of 1029 individuals, AA occurred 342 times, Aa 500 times, and aa 187 times. Maximize the loglikelihood and find the MLE of \(\theta\).

Click for the answer
  1. Let \(X_0\), \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) denote the counts of AA, Aa and aa, respectively. The likelihood is

\[\text{lik}(\theta) = \left(1-\theta\right)^{2X_0} \left(2 \theta (1-\theta)\right)^{X_1} \theta^{2X_2} \]

The log likelihood is \[ \begin{align*} \text{loglik}(\theta) &= 2X_0 \log(1 - \theta) + X_1\log(2) + X_1 \log(\theta) + X_1 \log(1-\theta) + 2X_2\log(\theta)\\ &= X_1\log(2) + (X_1+2X_2) \log(\theta) + (2X_0 +X_1) \log(1 - \theta) \end{align*} \] We can take the derivative as \[ \begin{align*} \text{loglik}'(\theta) &= \frac{X_1+2X_2}\theta -\frac{2X_0 +X_1}{1 - \theta} \end{align*} \]

Setting to zero, we get

\[ \begin{align*} \frac{X_1+2X_2}\theta -\frac{2X_0 +X_1}{1 - \theta} &= 0 \\ (X_1+2X_2)(1-\theta) &= (2X_0 +X_1) \theta \\ X_1+2X_2 &= (2X_0 + 2 X_1 + 2 X_2)\theta \\ \frac{X_1+2X_2}{2X_0 + 2 X_1 + 2 X_2} &= \theta \end{align*} \]

In our data \(\theta = (2*187 + 500)/(2*1029) = 0.425\).

\(~\)

5.1.0.3 Exercise

With every 5 euros spent on groceries, you get a card with a picture of a dutch soccer player. One soccer fan is only interested in pictures of Memphis Depay. After collecting 23 pictures of undistinguished players, he gets his first Memphis! Write down the likelihood, and compute the MLE of the probability of getting a Memphis.

Click for the answer
  1. The “appropriate” distribution is the Geometric distribution. The likelihood is \[ {\rm likelihood}(p) = (1-p)^{23}p \] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(p) = 23 \log(1-p) + \log(p)\] Taking the derivative with respect to p \[ {\rm loglikelihood'}(p) = -23/(1-p) + 1/p = (-24p + 1)/p(1-p)\] Setting equal to zero, we get \(p=1/24=0.0417.\)

\(~\)

5.1.0.4 Exercise

During a thunderstorm, the weather service counts the number of lightning flashes in 5 subsequent 1 minute intervals. They find 17, 25, 17, 18, and 15 flashes. Write down the likelihood, and compute the MLE of the expectation lambda.

Click for the answer

The “appropriate” distribution is the Poisson distribution. The likelihood is \[ {\rm likelihood}(\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^5 \frac{\lambda^{x(i)}}{x(i)!} e^{-\lambda} \] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^5 \left( x(i) \log(\lambda) - \log(x(i)!) -\lambda \right)\] The derivative with respect to lambda is \[ {\rm loglikelihood'}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^5 x(i)/\lambda - n\] Setting equal to zero, we find \(\hat \lambda = \sum_{i=1}^5 x(i) / n\)

mean(c(17, 25, 17, 18, 15))
## [1] 18.4

\(~\)

5.1.0.5 Exercise

A manufacturer tests 10 light bulbs and records how many months they burn continuously before burning out. She finds 8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9 and 3.1 months. Write down the likelihood, and compute the MLE of the expected number of burning months.

Click for the answer

The “appropriate” distribution is the Exponential distribution. The Exponential distribution is parametrized by the “rate” lambda, which is the reciprocal of the expected waiting time. So, we’ll estimate lambda, and then take the reciprocal. The likelihood is

\[ {\rm likelihood}(\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^{10} \lambda e^{-\lambda x(i)}\] The log likelihood is \[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^{10} [ \log(\lambda) - \lambda x(i) ]\] The derivative with respect to lambda is \[ {\rm loglikelihood'}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^{10} [1/\lambda - x(i) ] = 10/\lambda - \sum_{i=1}^{10} x(i)\] Setting equal to zero, we find \(\hat \lambda = 10 / \sum_{i=1}^{10} x(i)\). So for the expected waiting time we find \(1/\hat \lambda = \sum_{i=1}^{10} x(i)/10\)

mean(c(8.5, 2.3, 11.0, 22.5, 13.6, 5.8, 27.3, 13.1, 0.9, 3.1))
## [1] 10.81

\(~\)

5.1.0.6 Exercise

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find (in grams) \(X_1=983,\ X_2=1041,\ X_3=1026,\ X_4=1025,\ X_5=1033,\ X_6=968,\ X_7=1028\). Suppose we know that the (population) standard deviation of the weights is 25 grams. Write down the likelihood, and compute the MLE of the population average.

Click for the answer
  1. The “appropriate” distribution is the normal distribution. The likelihood is:

\[ {\rm likelihood}(\mu) = \prod_{i=1}^{7} \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{-(x(i) - \mu)^2/2\sigma^2}\] The log likelihood is

\[ {\rm loglikelihood}(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^{7} [ -\log(\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}) - (x(i)-\mu)^2/2\sigma^2 ]\] Taking the derivative with respect to \(\mu\)

\[ {\rm loglikelihood'}(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^{7} [ (x(i) - \mu)/\sigma^2]\] Setting equal to zero, we get \(\mu = \sum_{i=1}^{7}x(i)/7\).

mean(c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028))
## [1] 1014.857

\(~\)

5.1.0.7 Exercise

The “lasso” is a very popular method in machine learning and statistics. It is based on the Laplace distribution, which is also known as the double exponential distribution. This distribution has the following density \[f_\theta(x) = \frac{1}{2\theta} e^{-|x-\mu|/\theta} \qquad (\theta>0)\] Suppose we observe x=c(-4.77,5.52,-0.38,1.13,21.86,-13.79,-12.61,-1.01,13.96,2.37), and that \(\mu=0\) is known. What is the maximum likelihood estimator of \(\theta\)?

Click for the answer

The likelihood is: \[ {\rm likelihood}(\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{2\theta} e^{-|x_i|/\theta}\]

and the log likelihood is \[{\rm loglikelihood}(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (-\log(2\theta) - |x_i|/\theta) = -n\log(2\theta) - \frac1\theta \sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i|\] We take the derivative

\[{\rm loglikelihood}'(\theta) = -\frac n\theta + \frac1{\theta^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i|.\] Setting to zero, we have \[ \frac n\theta = \frac1{\theta^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i|,\] which we solve as \(\theta = \frac1n \sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i|\).

x=c(-4.77,5.52,-0.38,1.13,21.86,-13.79,-12.61,-1.01,13.96,2.37)
mean(abs(x))
## [1] 7.74

\(~\)

5.1.0.8 Exercise

Continuing from the previous exercise, suppose that \(\theta=5\) is known. Make a plot of the log likelihood of \(\mu\). Do you think you can find the MLE by differentiating? If not, why?

Click for the answer

The likelihood is: \[ {\rm likelihood}(\mu) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{10} e^{-|x_i-\mu|/5}\]

and the log likelihood is \[{\rm loglikelihood}(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (-\log(10) - |x_i-\mu|/5) = -n\log(10) - \frac15 \sum_{i=1}^{n}|x_i-\mu|\]

x=c(-4.77,5.52,-0.38,1.13,21.86,-13.79,-12.61,-1.01,13.96,2.37)
n = length(x)
theta=5
loglik = function(mu) -n*log(2*theta) - sum(abs(x-mu))/theta
mu = seq(-3, 3, by=.001)
plot(mu, sapply(mu, loglik), type='l')

We cannot find the MLE by differentiating, because it the curve is angular rather than smooth (``not differentiable’’) and has a completely flat top.

\(~\)

Setting the derivative of the log likelihood equal to zero often works to find the MLE, but not always!

5.1.0.9 Exercise

Suppose we have a sample \(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_{5}\) from the uniform distribution on \([0,\theta]\).

  1. Start by writing down the likelihood.

  2. Now, we generate some data:

set.seed(123)

Plot the likelihood. Find the MLE of \(\theta\) both with pen-and-paper and with R.

Click for the answer

  1. The likelihood is just \[ {\rm likelihood}(\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{5} \frac{1}{\theta}=1/\theta^5\] when \(\theta\) is greater than the maximum of the \(x(i)\), and zero otherwise!

  2. Now generate some data

set.seed(123)
x=runif(5,0,3.14)
theta=seq(0,6,0.001)
lik=(theta > max(x))*(1/theta)^5

# The MLE is max(x)
max(x)
## [1] 2.953067

5.2 The (log) likelihood is random

Given a model, we can calculate a likelihood for a data set. Suppose we have data that we can assume to come from an exponential distribution.

X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
lambda <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
loglik <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun) 
plot(lambda, loglik, type='l')

However, since the likelihood-function depends on the data, it has a sampling distribution. Every time we generate new data, we have a different likelihood.

plot(1, type="n", xlim=0:1, ylim=c(-60,-10), xlab="p", ylab="log likelihood")
funs <- replicate(20, { 
  X <- rexp(12, rate=1/4)
  loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(log(dexp(X, rate=lambda)))
  lambda <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
  loglik <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun) 
  lines(lambda, loglik)
})

The randomness of the likelihood is something you should keep in mind during the rest of this lecture. It means that most things we calculate from the likelihood are also random.

\(~\)

5.2.0.1 Exercise

Visualize the sampling distribution of the log likelihood of \(p\) when sampling 12 Bernoulli variables with a true probability of 0.3. Draw 20 random curves. Why are there less than 20 lines in the plot you have just made? Why do all the log likelihoods intersect when \(p=0.5\)?

Click for the answer 
plot(1, type="n", xlim=0:1, ylim=c(-40,0), xlab="p", ylab="log likelihood")
funs <- replicate(20, { 
  X <- rbinom(12, size=1, prob=0.3)
  loglik.fun <- function(p) sum(log(dbinom(X, size = 1, prob=p)))
  p <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
  loglik <- sapply(p, loglik.fun) 
  lines(p, loglik)
})

There are fewer than 20 lines in this plot, because the likelihood depends only on the number of observed successes in the data. This means that there are at most 13 possible shapes for the likelihood (for 0, 1,…, 12 observed successes). We do not see all 13 because some of these curves have very low probability of occurring (e.g. 12 successes will almost never happen if \(p=0,3\).

All curves intersect at \(p=0.5\) because when \(p=0.5\) the probability of each realization of the data (all sequences e.g. \((0,1,1,0,..., 1)\) is the same. The value of the likelihood at that point, therefore, does not depend on the data.

\(~\)

5.3 Derivatives of the log likelihood

When studying a log likelihood, we are not always so much interested in the function itself, as in its derivatives. When calculating the maximum likelihood estimate analytically, we find the first derivative of the log likelihood and find the MLE as the location where the derivative is zero. The first derivative of the log likelihood is also known as the score function or just the score. Let’s look at the score in more detail.

We take the exponential likelihood as an example. The exponential density is \[f(x) = \lambda e^{-\lambda x}.\] The log of this density is \[\log f(x) = \log(\lambda) + \log( e^{-\lambda x}) = \log(\lambda) - \lambda x.\] The log likelihood is therefore \[\mathrm{loglik}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^n \big(\log(\lambda) - \lambda x_i\big) \\ = n\log(\lambda) - \lambda \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] Let’s visualize the log likelihood. Suppose we have data \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) that we can assume to come from an exponential distribution.

X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
lambda <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
loglik <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun) 
plot(lambda, loglik, type='l')

To find the score we take the derivative with respect to \(\lambda\): \[\mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = \frac{n}{\lambda} - \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\]

The score is very useful for calculating the maximum likelihood estimate. We find the maximum likelihood estimate by finding the value of \(\lambda\) where the score is zero. In this case \(\hat\lambda\) is the value such that \[\mathrm{loglik}'(\hat\lambda) = \frac{n}{\hat\lambda} - \sum_{i=1}^n x_i = 0,\] so \[\hat\lambda = n/\Big(\sum_{i=1}^n x_i\Big) = 1/\bar X\].

Recipe for finding the MLE analytically

  1. Find the density \(f(x)\) of your model
  2. Calculate \(\log f (x)\)
  3. Find the log likelihood as \(\sum_{i=1}^n\log f(x_i)\)
  4. Calculate the score by differentiating the log likelihood
  5. Find the value of the parameter where the score is zero

To find the score for a likelihood, it is helpful to review the most important rules of differentiation:

\[\begin{align*} f(x) = x^k \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = kx^{k-1} \\ f(x) = e^x \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = e^x \\ f(x) = \log(x) \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = 1/x \quad \textrm{(for $x>0$)}\\ f(x) = ag(x) \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = ag'(x) \\ f(x) = g(x) + h(x) \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = g'(x) + h'(x) \qquad (\textrm{sum rule}) \\ f(x) = g(x)h(x) \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = g'(x)h(x) + g(x)h'(x) \qquad \textrm{(product rule)}\\ f(x) = g[h(x)] \quad &\to \quad f'(x) = g'[h(x)]h'(x) \qquad \textrm{(chain rule)} \end{align*}\]

\(~\)

5.3.0.1 Exercise

Explain the steps of the derivation of the score of the exponential distribution.

Click for the answer

We use that the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives. Then the derivative of \(\log(\lambda)\) is \(1/\lambda\), and the derivative of \(\lambda\) is 1.

\(~\)

Let us visualize this score of the exponential distribution log likelihood.

X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
score.fun <- function(lambda) length(X)/ lambda - sum(X)
lambda <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
score <- sapply(lambda, score.fun) 
plot(lambda, score, type='l', ylim=c(-50,200))
abline(h=0, col="grey")

In this course we will only encounter well-behaved likelihoods that have a single maximum. In this case the score will give useful information:

  • score(\(\lambda\)) \(>0\): \(\lambda\) is below the MLE
  • score(\(\lambda\)) \(=0\): \(\lambda\) is the MLE
  • score(\(\lambda\)) \(<0\): \(\lambda\) is above the MLE

\(~\)

5.3.0.2 Exercise

We did not mention the quotient rule

\[f(x) = g(x)/h(x) \quad \quad \to \quad f'(x) = \frac{h(x)g'(x) - h'(x)g(x)}{h^2(x)}.\]

Derive this rule by writing \(f(x) = g(x)\frac{1}{h(x)}\) and applying the product and chain rules.

Click for the answer

Write

\[\begin{align*} f(x) &= g'(x) \frac{1}{h(x)} + g(x) \Big(\frac{1}{h(x)}\Big)' \\ &= \frac{g'(x)}{h(x)} + g(x) \frac{-1}{h^2(x)} h'(x) \\ &= \frac{g'(x)h(x)}{h^2(x)} - \frac{g(x)h'(x)}{h^2(x)} \\ &= \frac{h(x)g'(x) - g(x)h'(x)}{h^2(x)} \end{align*}\]

Where we use the product rule in the first step and the chain rule in the second.

\(~\)

5.3.0.3 Exercise

Calculate the score for the likelihood of \(p\) in the Belgian euro experiment with \(N=250\).

Click for the answer

There are two equivalent ways of viewing this problem. One is as a sequence of Bernoulli trials. The other as a single binomial. Let’s do them both and see that they indeed give the same result.

If we see the coin toss as a sequence of Bernoulli trials, we observe \(T = (T_1, \ldots, T_n)\), where each \(T_i\) is 0 or 1 depending on whether we observe heads (1) or tails (0). The density is \[f(x) = p^x(1-p)^{(1-x)},\] so the log density is \[\log f(x) = x \log(p) + (1-x) \log(1-p).\] The log likelihood is \[\textrm{loglik}(p) = \sum_{i=1}^N \{ t_i \log(p) + (1-t_i) \log(1-p) \} = \log(p) \sum_{i=1}^N t_i + \log(1-p) \sum_{i=1}^N (1-t_i).\] If \(X\) is the number of heads, this is the same as \[\textrm{loglik}(p) = \log(p) X + \log(1-p) (N-X).\] The derivative of \(\log(p)\) is \(1/p\) and the derivative of \(\log(1-p)\) is \(-1/(1-p)\) by the chain rule, so the score is \[\textrm{loglik}'(p) = X/p - (N-X)/(1-p).\]

With \(N=250\) and \(X=140\), this is \[\textrm{loglik}'(p) = 140/p - 110/(1-p).\]

If, on the other hand we see the experiment as resulting in a single obervation \(X\) Binomial distribution with parameters \(N\) and \(p\), the density is \[ f(x) = {N \choose x} p^x(1-p)^{(N-x)}.\] The log density is \[ log f(x) = \log {N \choose x} + \log(p) x + \log(1-p) (N-x),\] so this is also the log likelihood \[\textrm{loglik}(p) = \log {N \choose x} + \log(p) x + \log(1-p) (N-x).\] Differentiating with respect to \(p\), the first term drops out and we get exactly the same score.

\(~\)

5.3.0.4 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Calculate the score as a function of \(\lambda\).

Click for the answer

The Poisson density is \(f(x) = e^{-\lambda} \lambda^x/x!\), so the log density is \(\log f(x) = -\lambda + x\log(\lambda) - \log(x!)\). The log likelihood is therefore \[ \mathrm{loglik}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^n \{-\lambda + x_i\log(\lambda) - \log(x_i!)\} \\ = -n\lambda + \log(\lambda) \sum_{i=1}^n x_i - \sum_{i=1}^n \log(x_i!).\] Differentiating, we obtain

\[ \mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = -n + \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i = 21/\lambda - 10.\]

\(~\)

We can also find the score by doing the differentiation of the log likelihood numerically. Remember the definition of the derivative \[f'(x) = \lim_{t\to 0}\frac{f(x+t)-f(x)}{t}.\]

Numerically, instead of taking \(t \to 0\) all the way, we can just take \(t\) very small: we divide the increments of the log likelihood by the increments of \(\lambda\). The finer a grid you take for lambda, the more accurate the numerical approximation.

X <- c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda, log=TRUE))
step <- 0.001
lambda <- seq(0,5,by=step)
loglik <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun) 
score <- diff(loglik)/step
plot(lambda[-length(lambda)], score, type='l', ylim=c(-50,200), xlab='lambda')
abline(h=0, col="grey")

We can add the exact score function in red:

plot(lambda[-length(lambda)], score, type='l', ylim=c(-50,200), xlab='lambda')
abline(h=0, col="grey")
lines(lambda, 21/lambda-10,col="red")  # exact score

\(~\)

5.3.0.5 Exercise

For the Belgian euro experiment, calculate the score numerically, and compare your result to the analytic result you found earlier by plotting the score calculated in both ways.

Click for the answer 
loglik.fun <- function(p) sum(dbinom(140, size=250, prob=p, log=TRUE))
step <- 0.001
p <- seq(0,1,by=step)
loglik <- sapply(p, loglik.fun) 
score.numeric <- diff(loglik)/step
score.analytic <- 140/p - 110/(1-p)
plot(p[-length(p)], score.numeric, type='l', xlab='p', ylim=c(-1000,1000))
lines(p, score.analytic, col='red')
abline(h=0, col="grey")

\(~\)

5.3.0.6 Exercise

The following values were oberved from a normal distribution with known mean \(\mu=0\) and unknown \(\sigma^2\): \(X=( 0.06, 0.21, 0.47, -2.48, -0.39, -1.11)\). Calculate and plot the score for \(\sigma^2\) numerically. Read off the approximate maximum likelihood estimate from your plot.

To read off the MLE you may want to further reduce the ylim, or we calculate something like

sig2[which.min(abs(score))]

\(~\)

5.4 What have we learned?

  • We can calculate the MLE analytically
  • We can calculate score analytically and numerically.
  • We can use the score to find maximum likelihood estimators.

6 Large Sample Theory

When the sample size is large, many statistical calculations simplify. In this lecture we explain why that is so. In practice, we must often rely on these simplifications because otherwise the calculations are just too difficult. Of course, this is only valid if our sample size is “large enough”.

6.1 LLN and CLT

For statistics, the two most important results of probability theory are the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) and the Central Limit Theorem (CLT).

\(~\)

6.1.0.1 Exercise

Run the following script at least 10 times and comment what you see.

x=rnorm(100,2,1)
xbar=cumsum(x)/(1:100)     # check: ?cumsum
plot(1:100,xbar,type="l")
abline(h=2)
Click for the answer

We see the cumulative average of standard normal random variables becoming less variable and “converging” to the mean. This is an illustration of the law of large numbers.

\(~\)

The LLN says that averages converge to means (expected values). We have used the LLN to motivate the method of moments. Since many estimators (inclusing MLEs) are basically just averages, the LLN often implies that an estimator converges to the true parameter as the sample size increases. This is called “consistency” or asymptotic unbiasedness. Here , asymptotic means “for very large sample size”. Consistency is often viewed as the minimal requirement for a sensible estimator.

The Central Limit Theorem is a deeper result than the LLN. The CLT says that sums and averages become normally distributed. This means that as the sample size increases, many different estimation problems start to resemble estimating the simple situation of estimating the mean of a normal distribution by the sample average. The following exercise demonstrates the CLT.

\(~\)

6.1.0.2 Exercise

  1. Use runif to generate a sample of size 10^5 from the standard uniform distribution, and make a histogram.
  2. Generate another sample of size 10^5 from the standard uniform distribution, and add this to your first sample. Again, make a histogram.
  3. Generate another sample of size 10^5 from the standard uniform distribution, and add this to the first two samples. Again, make a histogram.
  4. Keep going!
Click for the answer 
u1=runif(10^5)
hist(u1,100)

u2=runif(10^5)
hist(u1+u2,100)

u3=runif(10^5)
hist(u1+u2+u3,100)

u4=runif(10^5)
hist(u1+u2+u3+u4,100)

After just 3 or 4 steps, we see the normal bell curve appear. This illustrates the Central Limit Theorem.

\(~\)

\(~\)

6.1.0.3 Exercise

Try the same steps as the previous exercise, but now use the exponential distribution.

Click for the answer 
x1=rexp(10^5)
hist(x1,100)

x2=rexp(10^5)
hist(x1+x2,100)

x3=rexp(10^5)
hist(x1+x2+x3,100)

x4=rexp(10^5)
hist(x1+x2+x3+x4,100)

Again, you can see the normal bell curve appear, but much slower than with the uniform distribution. This is due to the fact that the exponential distribution is so heavily skewed.

\(~\)

6.2 Estimating the mean of a normal distribution

Many “regular” estimators are basically just averages of some sort. The LLN tells us that averages converge to the expected value and therefore many estimators converge to the true parameter. The CLT tells us that averages become normally distributed as the sample size increases. This means that many estimators start to behave like the sample average of a normal distribution. So, let us look more closely at this archetype of statistical estimation.

Suppose we have an i.i.d. sample \(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n\) from a normal distribution with unknown mean \(\mu\) and known standard deviation \(\sigma\). We can run a little simulation by choosing \(n=12\), \(\mu=2\) and \(\sigma=1\). We plot the log likelihood.

X <- rnorm(12, mean=2, sd=1)
loglik.fun <- function(mu) sum(log(dnorm(X, mean=mu, sd=1)))
mu <- seq(0,4,by=0.01)
loglik <- sapply(mu, loglik.fun) 
plot(mu, loglik, type='l')

The log likelihood of the normal mean looks like a parabola (= quadratic function), and in fact it is! We can derive this analytically. Remember that the normal density is

\[f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}} e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2},\] and so

\[ \begin{align*} \log f(x) &= \log \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}} + \log \Big(e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2}\Big) \\ &= -\frac12 \log(2\pi\sigma^2) - \frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2 \\ &= -\frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \mu^2 + \frac{x}{\sigma^2}\mu - \frac{x^2}{2\sigma^2} - \frac12 \log(2\pi\sigma^2). \end{align*} \] We see that the log density of a normal distribution is a parabola in \(\mu\) because is has the form \(A \mu^2 + B\mu +C\).

\(~\)

6.2.0.1 Exercise

Explain the steps in this calculation.

Click for the answer

The first step uses \(\log(ab) = \log(a) + \log(b)\). The second \(\log(x^{-1/2}) = -\frac12\log(x)\) and \(\log(e^x) = x\). The third step expands \((x-\mu)^2=x^2+2x\mu+\mu^2\).

\(~\)

The log likelihood is also a parabola:

\[ \begin{align*} \mathrm{loglik}(\mu) &= \sum_{i=1}^n \Big( -\frac{1}{2\sigma^2} \mu^2 + \frac{x_i}{\sigma^2}\mu - \frac{x_i^2}{2\sigma^2} - \frac12 \log(2\pi\sigma^2)\Big) \\ &= -\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \mu^2 + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\mu - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2}{2\sigma^2} - \frac n2 \log(2\pi\sigma^2) \end{align*} \]

So, the log likelihood also has the form \(A\mu^2 + B\mu + C\). This a unique property of the normal distribution, and it will turn out to be very important.

Parabolas were covered very prominently in your secondary school. What do you remember?

  • If \(A<0\), the parabola has a maximum.
  • The location of that maximum is at \(-\frac{B}{2A}\).
  • If \(|A|\) is large, the function is very peaked, if \(|A|\) is small, it is flat

\(~\)

6.2.0.2 Exercise

  • Check that \(A<0\).
  • Check that the location of maximum of the log likelihood at \(-B/(2A)\) is equal to \(\bar X\).
  • What determines whether the normal log likelihood is very peaked?
Click for the answer
  • \(A = -\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} < 0\)
  • The MLE is at the maximum of the log likelihood, which is at -B/(2A). So, \[\hat\mu=-B/(2A) = -\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2} /\Big(-\frac{2n}{2\sigma^2}\Big) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{n} = \bar X\]
  • \(|A|=\frac{n}{2\sigma^2}\). So the log likelihood is peaked when \(n\) is large and/or \(\sigma^2\) is small.

\(~\)

We discussed derivatives of the log likelihood before. The score function is the first derivative of the log likelihood. In this case, the score is

\[\mathrm{loglik}'(\mu) = -\frac{n}{\sigma^2} \mu + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\] We can find the MLE of \(\mu\) by setting the score equal to zero, and then we find \(\hat \mu = \bar X = \frac 1n \sum_{i=1}^n x_i\). The second derivative is also very important.

\[\mathrm{loglik}''(\mu) = -\frac{n}{\sigma^2}.\] The first derivative is the rate of change of a function. So, the second derivative is the rate of change of the first derivative. In this case, it tells us how curved or “peaked” the log likelihood is. \(~\)

6.2.0.3 Exercise

Let us look at the log likelihood for different values of \(n\) and \(\sigma\). Run the following code for n=5,10,20 and 100, and sd=1,2 and 5.

n=5
sd=1
X <- rnorm(n=n, mean=0, sd=sd)
loglik.fun <- function(mu) sum(log(dnorm(X, mean=mu, sd=sd)))
mu <- seq(-10,10,by=0.01)
loglik <- sapply(mu, loglik.fun) 
plot(mu, loglik, type='l',xlim=c(-10,10),ylim=c(-200,10))
Click for the answer Note that the log likelihood is more “peaked” when \(n\) is large and/or \(\sigma\) is small.

\(~\)

If we have few data points (\(n\) is small) or our data are very noisy (\(\sigma\) is large) then we do not have very much information to estimate \(\mu\). In that case, the log likelihood is very flat so that values close to the MLE all have similar likelihood. That means we cannot tell those values for \(\mu\) apart on the basis of our data. In other words: the MLE is not well localized.

The following statements are different ways of saying the same thing about estimating the mean of a normal distribution:

  • The sample size (\(n\)) is small and the data are very noisy (\(\sigma\) is large).
  • We do not have much information about \(\mu\).
  • Minus the second derivative of the log likelihood is small.
  • The log likelihood is very flat.
  • The MLE is not well localized.

With this in mind, the definition of the Fisher information of a parameter \(\theta\) should make sense. The Fisher information is often denote by \(\cal I(\theta)\), and it is defined as the expectation of minus the second derivative of the log likelihood \[\textrm{Fisher Information}(\theta) = \cal I(\theta) = \mathrm{E}(-\mathrm{loglik}''(\theta)).\] We take the expectation because in general the log likelihood and its second derivative are random (they depend on the data). The (random) quantity \(I(\theta) = -\mathrm{loglik}''(\theta)\) is called the observed Fisher information.

Now, in the special case of estimating the mean of a normal distribution the second derivative of the log likelihood does not depend on the data. In fact, it does not even depend on \(\mu\)! We have \[{\cal I}(\mu) = I(\mu) = \frac{n}{\sigma^2}.\]

6.2.0.4 Exercise

The expression for \(\cal I(\mu)\) may not immediately be meaningful to you, but if you take \(1/\cal I(\mu)\), does that look familiar? Or \(1/\sqrt{\cal I (\mu)}\)? Where have you encountered that expression before?

Click for the answer

\(1/\sqrt{\cal I}(\mu) = \sigma/\sqrt{n}\) is the standard error of the mean \(\hat\mu\).

\(~\)

6.2.0.5 Exercise

Calculate the mean and standard deviation of \(\hat \mu = \frac1n \sum_{i=1}^n x_i\) if \(x_1, \ldots, x_n\) are iid normal with parameters \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^2\) (i.e. the standard error). What is the distribution of \(\hat\mu\)?

Click for the answer

\[ \mathrm{E}\Big( n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i \Big) = \frac1n \sum_{i=1}^n \mathrm{E}(x_i) = \mu \\ \mathrm{Var}\Big( n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i \Big) = \frac{1}{n^2}\sum_{i=1}^n \mathrm{Var}(x_i) = \sigma^2/n,\] Where the last calculation uses the fact that \(x_1,\ldots, x_n\) are independent.

Because the sum of independent normally distributed variables is normal, \(\hat\mu\) is also normal with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2/n\).

\(~\)

The Fisher Information is a very useful tool. It describes the amount of information there is in the likelihood (and therefore in the data) about the parameter. The larger the Fisher information, the more peaked the log likelihood, and the more precisely we can estimate the parameter.

6.3 Calculating the Fisher Information

The second derivative of the log likelihood governs how peaked the log likelihood is. Let’s calculate the second derivative for the exponential log likelihood. Recall that the density of the exponential distribution is \[f_\lambda(x) = \lambda e^{-\lambda x} \qquad \] where \(\lambda>0\) is the “rate”. If \(X\) has the exponential distribution, then the expected value is \(E(X)=1/\lambda\). If we have an i.i.d. sample then the score function (=derivative of the log likelihood) is \[\mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = \frac{n}{\lambda} - \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] Setting the score function equal to zero, we find the MLE \(\hat \lambda = 1/\bar X\). Differentiating again, we find the second derivative of the log likelihood \[\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda) = -\frac{n}{\lambda^2}.\]

Since \(\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)\) does not depend on the data, the Fisher Information \({\cal I}(\lambda)=\mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)]\) is equal to the observed Fisher information \(I(\lambda) = -\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)\). We have \[{\cal I}(\lambda) = I(\lambda) = \mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)] = \frac{n}{\lambda^2}\]

\(~\)

We see that the Fisher information \(n/\lambda^2\) decreases steeply as \(\lambda\) increases, but increases with \(n\). We learn from this (1) that larger sample sizes will have more information and give more accurate estimates and (2) that large values of \(\lambda\) have less information and are more difficult to estimate precisely.

6.3.0.1 Exercise

Calculate the observed Fisher information and the Fisher information for for a single draw \(X\) from the binomial distribution with known sample size \(n\) and unknown probability of success \(p\). Is there a difference between observed Fisher information and Fisher information?

Click for the answer

We found the score as \[\mathrm{loglik}'(p) = \frac{X}{p} - \frac{N-X}{1-p}.\] Differentiating, we get the observed Fisher information \[\mathrm{loglik}''(p) = -\frac{X}{p^2} - \frac{N-X}{(1-p)^2}.\] This still depends on the data, so the observed Fisher information is \[I(p) = -\mathrm{loglik}''(p) = \frac{X}{p^2} + \frac{N-X}{(1-p)^2}.\]

Since this depends on the data, there is a difference with the Fisher information. We calculate that as \[ \begin{align*} {\cal I}(p) = \mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(p)] &= \frac{\mathrm{E}(X)}{p^2} + \frac{N-\mathrm{E}(X)}{(1-p)^2} \\ &= \frac{Np}{p^2} + \frac{N(1-p)}{(1-p)^2} \\ &= \frac{N}{p} + \frac{N}{(1-p)} \\ &= \frac{N(1-p)}{p(1-p)} + \frac{Np}{p(1-p)} \\ &= \frac{N}{p(1-p)}. \end{align*} \]

\(~\)

6.3.0.2 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Calculate the Fisher Information analytically.

Click for the answer

We found the score as \[ \mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = -n + \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] Differentiating, we get the observed Fisher information \[\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda) = -\lambda^{-2} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] This still depends on the data, so there is a difference between observed Fisher Information and Fisher information. We calculate the latter as \[\mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)] = \lambda^{-2} \mathrm{E}\Big[\sum_{i=1}^n x_i\Big] = \lambda^{-2} n\lambda = n/\lambda. \]

\(~\)

Like the score, we can calculate the observed Fisher Information numerically, simply by numerically differentiating twice.

X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
step <- 0.001
lambda <- seq(0,1,by=step)
loglik <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun) 
score <- diff(loglik)/step
FisherInfo <- -diff(score)/step
plot(lambda[-c(1,length(lambda))], FisherInfo, type='l', ylim=c(0,200), 
     xlab = 'lambda')

Alternatively, we can use the function hessian from the numDeriv package which computes the second derivative of a function.

library(numDeriv)
X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
lambda <- seq(0.1,1,by=0.01)
H=sapply(lambda, function(lambda) hessian(loglik.fun,lambda))
FisherInfo=-H   # Observed Fisher information = - second derivative of the score (log lik)
plot(lambda, FisherInfo, type='l', ylim=c(0,200), xlab = 'lambda')

\(~\)

6.4 Large sample theory

The Central Limit Theorem says that if some random variable is the sum of many random variables, its distribution will tend towards the normal distribution. The CLT also works on the log likelihood itself, which is random and (in case of independent observations) the sum of many terms, one for each subject.

\[\text{loglik}(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^N \log f_\theta(X_i).\]

The CLT also works on important quantities that we calculate from the log likelihood, such as the MLE and the Fisher information.

6.4.0.1 Exercise

Explain using the law of large numbers that the observed Fisher Information, divided by \(N\), gets closer and closer to the Fisher Information, divided by \(N\), as \(N\) increases. Hint: write the observed Fisher Information as a sum of many terms.

Click for the answer

The log likelihood is \(\text{loglik}(\theta) = \sum_{i=1}^N \log f_\theta(X_i)\). Because the derivative of a sum is a sum of derivatives, the observed Fisher information is \[I(\theta) = -\text{loglik}''(\theta) = - \sum_{i=1}^N \log f_\theta''(X_i)\]

where ’’ here means derivation with respect to the parameter \(\theta\). By the LLN we have that the average of i.i.d. random variables converges to its expectation, so \[ \begin{align*} \frac1N I(\theta) = - \frac1N \sum_{i=1}^N \log f_\theta''(X_i) \rightarrow & - E\left[\log f_\theta''(X_1)\right] \\ & = - \frac1N\sum_{i=1}^N E\left[ \log f_\theta''(X_i)\right] \\ & = - \frac1N E\left[\sum_{i=1}^N \log f_\theta''(X_i)\right]\\ & = \frac1N E[-\text{loglik}''(\theta)] = \frac1N {\cal I}(\theta). \end{align*} \]

\(~\)

So, loosely speaking, if the sample size is large, everything we would calculate starts to look like it comes from a normal distribution likelihood.

We can demonstrate this with an example about the binomial distribution. In the next chapter, we’ll meet two Polish researchers who tested a Belgian euro coin for fairness. They tossed the coin 250 times to get an estimate of the probability \(p\) of heads. They obtained heads 140 times, so their estimate was 140/250.

We already know that estimates get more and more accurate as the sample size increases but how do we see this in the log likelihood? Let’s compare the log likelihood for the same estimate (\(\hat p = 14/25=0.56\)) for sample sizes of 25, 250, 2500, 25000…

loglik.fun25 <- function(p) dbinom(14, size = 25, prob=p, log=TRUE)
loglik.fun250 <- function(p) dbinom(140, size = 250, prob=p, log=TRUE)
loglik.fun2500 <- function(p) dbinom(1400, size = 2500, prob=p, log=TRUE)
loglik.fun25000 <- function(p) dbinom(14000, size = 25000, prob=p, log=TRUE)
p <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
plot(p, loglik.fun25(p), type='l', ylab='loglik')
lines(p, loglik.fun250(p), col='red')
lines(p, loglik.fun2500(p), col='blue')
lines(p, loglik.fun25000(p), col='green')

What do we notice? First, while the top of the log likelihood remains in the same place at 0.56, the log likelihood becomes much more “peaked”. With larger sample size, the log likelihood drops much more steeply as we move away from the maximum. Take for example the value \(p=0.6\). The log likelihood of that value is about the same as that of the MLE of \(0.56\) when \(N=25\), a bit smaller when \(N=250\), substantially smaller when \(N=2500\), and a lot smaller if \(N=25000\). The more peaked the log likelihood is, the better it is able to distinguish between likely and less likely values of the parameter \(p\). Intuitively, this means that a peaked log likelihood gives more accurate estimates.

Second, we see that as \(N\) increases, the log likelihood looks more and more like a parabola. In the example, the log likelihood is already very much like a parabola when \(N=250\). This phenomenon is not specific to the binomial log likelihood we use here, but holds for all well-behaved log likelihoods (we’ll discuss what that well-behaved means later). This means that for large \(N\), rather than writing down a complicated log likelihood, we may instead write down a much simpler one: the log likelihood function of a normal distribution!

Let us consider another example. Suppose we have an i.i.d. sample from the exponential distribution. We generate some data for different sample sizes, and plot the log likelihood. Note that we align the log likelihood functions vertically, so that we can compare them more easily.

set.seed(1234)
X <- rexp(1e4, rate=1/4)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda, N) sum(dexp(X[1:N], rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
lambda <- seq(0,1,by=0.001)
loglik1 <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun, N=10)
loglik2 <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun, N=1e2)
loglik3 <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun, N=1e3)
loglik4 <- sapply(lambda, loglik.fun, N=1e4)
plot(lambda, loglik1-max(loglik1), type='l', ylab='loglik', ylim=c(-10,0))
lines(lambda, loglik2-max(loglik2), col='red')
lines(lambda, loglik3-max(loglik3), col='blue')
lines(lambda, loglik4-max(loglik4), col='green')

Notice how, as the sample size \(N\) increases, the log likelihood

  • becomes more and more peaked, and
  • starts to look more and more like a parabola.

The log likelihood summarizes all the information we have to estimate some parameter. If the log likelihood looks very much like a parabola, and the parabola is the log likelihood of the mean of a normal distribution, then it follows that our estimation problem looks very much like estimating the mean of a normal distribution. This is a general principle, for which we will see many more applications later in this course.

One of the most important aspects we can “borrow” from the normal distribution likelihood is the distribution of the MLE. Remember that in a normal model, the MLE \(\hat\mu = \bar X\) has a normal distribution with mean \(\mu\) and variance equal to \(\sigma^2/n = 1/\cal I(\lambda)\).

What holds for the normal mean also holds for other well-behaved MLEs. If the sample size is large (we say: “asymptotically”) we have for the MLE \(\hat \theta\) of a parameter \(\theta\)

  • The MLE \(\hat \theta\) is asymptotically unbiased (i.e. “consistent”)
  • The MLE \(\hat \theta\) is asymptotically normal with mean \(\theta\)
  • The asymptotic variance of the MLE is \(1/\cal I(\theta)\)

The asymptotic variance may depend on the true \(\theta\) which is unknown. That is not a major problem in practice. We can simply plug in the MLE \(\hat\theta\) as we did with the bootstrap. So, for large \(N\), we can approximate the asymptotic variance of the MLE by \(1/\cal I(\hat \theta)\).

We will now demonstrate the asymptotic distribution of the MLE. Suppose, again, that we have an i.i.d. sample \(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_N\) from the exponential distribution and we want to estimate the rate parameter \(\lambda\). As we have seen, the exponential likelihood is indistinguishable from a normal likelihood if \(N\) is large.

So, for large \(N\), the distribution of the MLE \(\hat\lambda=1/\bar X\) converges to a normal distribution with mean \(\lambda\) and variance \(1/{\cal I} (\lambda)= \lambda^2/N\). We call this the asymptotic distribution of \(\hat\lambda\).

Let’s compare the true (simulated) distribution of the MLE \(\hat \lambda\) to the asymptotic distribution in an example.

true_lambda <- 1/4
N <- 50
K <- 1e4
hat_lambda <- numeric(true_lambda)
for (i in 1:K) {
  X <- rexp(N, rate = 1/4)
  hat_lambda[i] <- 1/mean(X)
}
asymptotic_mean <- true_lambda
asymptotic_sd <- sqrt(true_lambda^2/N)
hist(hat_lambda, 100, prob=TRUE)           # simulated distribution of the MLE
x=seq(0.1,0.4,0.001)
lines(x,dnorm(x, asymptotic_mean, asymptotic_sd))  # asymptotic (normal) distr.

\(~\)

6.4.0.2 Exercise

Both the simulated distribution (histogram) and the asymptotic normal distribution are approximations to the true distribution of \(\hat \lambda\).

  1. How can we make the asymptotic distribution more accurate?
  2. How can we make the simulated distribution more accurate?
Click for the answer

The asymptotic distribution becomes more accurate as the sample size (\(N\)) increases. The simulated distribution becomes more accurate as the number of simulation iterations (\(K\)) increases.

\(~\)

Suppose the Belgian euro coin is unbiased \(p=0.5\). What is the asymptotic sampling distribution of its estimate if we toss it \(N=250\) times? According to this asymptotic distribution, what is the probability that we find \(\hat p > 0.56\)?

Click for the answer

We found the Fisher Information to be \(N/\{p(1-p)\}\). Asymptotically, \(\hat p\) is normally distributed with mean \(p = 0.5\) and variance \(p(1-p)/N = 0.5^2/250\). We calculate

pnorm(0.56, mean=0.5, sd = sqrt(0.5^2/250), lower.tail=FALSE) 
## [1] 0.02888979

6.4.0.5 Exercise

Suppose the Belgian euro coin is unbiased with \(p=0.5\). Draw the simulated and the asymptotic distribution for the experiment of tossing the coin \(N=250\) times. Are the two distributions alike? Redraw, varying \(N\). From which value of \(N\) do you think the correspondence between the distributions is excellent?

Click for the answer 
true_p <- 1/2
N <- 500
K <- 1e4
hat_p <- numeric(K)
for (i in 1:K) {
  X <- rbinom(1, size =N, prob = true_p)
  hat_p[i] <- X/N
}
asymptotic_mean <- true_p
asymptotic_sd <- sqrt(true_p*(1-true_p)/N)

\(~\)

For very easy problems, we can calculate the Fisher information analytically by differentiation. In more complicated situations, we can do the calculation numerically. Remember that we only need to calculate the Fisher Information at the MLE. As before, we can use the diff function twice, or we can use the function hessian from the numDeriv package.

X <- c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik.fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
step <- 0.0001
hat_lambda <- 1/mean(X)
grid <- hat_lambda + c(-step,0,step)   # we make a small grid around the MLE
loglik <- sapply(grid, loglik.fun) 
score <- diff(loglik)/step
FisherInfo <- -diff(score)/step
FisherInfo
## [1] 109.2033

Alternatively, use hessian

H=hessian(loglik.fun,hat_lambda)
FisherInfo=-H
FisherInfo
##          [,1]
## [1,] 109.2033
#compare the analytic result
N <- length(X)
N/hat_lambda^2
## [1] 109.2033

\(~\)

6.4.0.6 Exercise

Explain what happens in the R code above.

Click for the answer

By calculating the log likelihood in the MLE itself and a small step below and above, we have a small grid around the MLE. Then we can take the difference and obtain the score just before and just after the MLE. Then taking the difference between these two scores, we obtain the second derivative.

\(~\)

6.4.0.8 Exercise

The values \(X = (9.99, 0.65, 31.93, 8.39, 0.58, 0.08)\) were observed from a lognormal distribution with unknown parameter \(\mu\) and unknown parameter \(\sigma^2=1\). Find the maximum likelihood estimate for \(\sigma^2\) numerically using the lognormal density. Find the Fisher information at the MLE numerically. What is the asymptotic distribution of the MLE?

hat_mu
## [1] 0.7318221
step <- 0.0001
grid <- hat_mu + c(-step,0,step)   # we make a small grid around the MLE
loglik <- sapply(grid, loglik.fun) 
score <- diff(loglik)/step
FisherInfo <- -diff(score)/step
FisherInfo
## [1] 6
# with hessian
H=hessian(loglik.fun,hat_mu)
FisherInfo=-H
FisherInfo
##      [,1]
## [1,]    6

We find that the MLE \(\hat\mu\) is asymptotically normal with mean \(0.73\) and standard error approximately \(1/\sqrt{6}\).

\(~\)

Asymptotic results such as the one we discussed about the distribution of the MLE are useful when the sample is “large”. How large should \(N\) be for the results to be used? There is no hard-and-fast results here, but some considerations and rules-of-thumb.

The consideration is that the more the distribution of the data differs from normality, the longer it takes (i.e. the larger \(N\) needs to be) for the distribution of the MLE to be similar to a normal distribution. Distributions tend to take long to converge if they are very skewed or have extreme outliers. For example, the exponential distribution with \(\lambda = 1/4\) we used as an example is very skewed, and it takes a relatively long time for the MLE to become nearly normal. We saw above that at \(N=50\) the distribution of the MLE was still appreciably different from a normal.

On the other hand, if a distribution is compact with few outliers, convergence to normality will be quick, as we have seen in the Belgian euro exercise above, with a binomial distribution with \(p=0.5\).

A reasonable rule of thumb might be that for most data distributions (not too skewed and not too many outliers) asymptotic approximations work quite well already when \(N=30\). Highly skewed distributions such as he exponential example will need about \(N=100\). For symmetric and compact distributions, \(N=10\) may already suffice. These are just loose guidelines of course; as with any approximation in statistics you must always check whether it is accurate enough in your data for the purposes you want to use it for.

6.5 Well-behaved likelihoods

All the theory we have given depends on the likelihood being “well-behaved”. This notion has to remain slightly vague or this would turn into a mathematical statistics course, but we will give you some intuition.

Let’s first have a look at an example of a not-so-well-behaved likelihood.

\(~\)

6.5.0.1 Exercise

Suppose our data are distributed according to a uniform distribution with parameters 0 and \(\theta\). Simulate \(1000\) data points with a true value of \(\theta=1\) and plot the log likelihood. Is it anything like a parabola?

Click for the answer 
X = runif(1e3, 0, 1)
loglik.fun <- function(theta) sum(dunif(X, 0, theta, log=TRUE))
grid <- seq(0,2,by=0.001)
loglik <- sapply(grid, loglik.fun) 
## Warning in dunif(X, 0, theta, log = TRUE): NaNs produced
plot(grid, loglik, type='l', xlab='theta')

Clearly nothing like a parabola.

\(~\)

We see that the log likelihood is not at all like a parabola. In general, loosely speaking, a likelihood is well-behaved if

  • the likelihood is sufficiently smooth around the value of the true parameter
  • the true value of the parameter is not at the edge of the parameter space

The uniform likelihood is an example that does not fulfil the first case: the (log) likelihood is not smooth, but has a sharp peak at \(\max(X_1, \ldots, X_n)\). An example of a likelihood not fulfilling the second case would be a normal likelihood when the true value of \(\sigma^2\) is 0.

With the exception of the uniform distribution, all models we’ve seen in this course lead to well-behaved likelihoods. The same holds for virtually all models that are frequently used in applied statistics. In this course, you may assume that every likelihood is well-behaved. If it isn’t (and it matters for the exercise), we’ll say so.

6.6 What have we learned?

  • We can describe the log likelihood of the normal distribution as a parabola.
  • We can use the asymptotic approximation to the log likelihood.
  • We can calculate the asymptotic distribution of maximum likelihood estimators.
  • We can explain the relationship between the Fisher Information and the peakedness of the log likelihood

7 Hypothesis testing

7.1 A fair coin?

A fair coin is such that when tossed, it comes up heads with probability 1/2. When the euro was introduced in 2002, Tomasz Gliszczynski and Waclaw Zawadowski, statistics teachers at the Akademia Podlaska in Siedlce tossed (or rather spun, to be precise) a Polish euro 10,000 times and did not find anything out of the ordinary. However, after flipping a Belgian euro \(n=250\) times, they found that it came up heads 140 times! They ascribe this deviation from 125 to the “portly” king Albert displayed on the Belgian euro (New Scientist, January 4, 2002).

7.1.0.1 Exercise

As a statistician, you must be able to assess the evidence for a claim. So, based on the data that were collected by the two researchers and your common sense, do you think the Belgian euro is fair?

Click for the answer We’ll see ;)

\(~\)

How should we decide this question? It is clear that – even if the coin is fair – getting exactly 125 heads in 250 tosses is unlikely. So some deviation from 125 is to be expected. It is also clear that if the coin is fair, getting 240 heads is virtually impossible. Getting 240 heads in 250 tosses surely makes it very doubtful that the coin is fair.

7.1.0.2 Exercise

Use \({\tt binom}\) to compute the probabilities of the two events mentioned above.

Click for the answer 
dbinom(125,250,0.5)
## [1] 0.05041221
dbinom(240,250,0.5)
## [1] 1.210475e-58

\(~\)

The only logical approach is to declare the coin unfair, if the deviation from 125 is larger than some cut-off. In other words, declare the coin unfair if \(|X-125|\) exceeds some cut-off.

7.1.0.3 Exercise

\(\dots\) or can you think of some other method?

Click for the answer Any reasonable method you can think of is probably equivalent to checking if |X-125| is large.

\(~\)

In statistical jargon, we have the following situation. Suppose \(X\) is distributed according to the Binomial distribution with sample size \(n=250\) and unknown \(p\). We want to test the null hypothesis \[H_0: p=1/2\] versus the alternative \[A: p\neq 1/2.\] We reject \(H_0\) if \(|X-125|\) exceeds some cut-off \(K\).

In this case, \(|X-125|\) is the test statistic and the cut-off \(K\) is its critical value. We still need to determine an appropriate value for \(K\) – we’ll get to that later.

The null hypothesis always represents the status quo or “nothing to report”. We reject it if there is enough evidence in favour of the alternative. If there is not enough evidence, then the null hypothesis gets the benefit of the doubt.

In other words, if we cannot reject the null hypothesis then we may not conclude that it is true. It only means that we do not have enough reason to doubt it. It can happen that the null hypothesis is totally false, but our sample size is too small to prove it.

Analogy Think of a court case. The accused (null hypothesis) is considered innocent until proven guilty.

The founding father of modern statistics, R.A. Fisher said it like this:

“The null hypothesis is never proved or established, but only disproved. (\(\dots\)) Every experiment may be said to exist only in order to give the facts a chance of disproving the null hypothesis.”

Our experiment to decide if a coin is fair is as follows: Flip the coin 250 times and record the number of heads \(X\). Reject the null hypothesis if \(|X-125| > K\). That is, we reject the null hypothesis if either \(X<125-K\) or \(X>125+K\). We still need to decide on an appropriate value of \(K\).

Below we show the probability that \(|X-125| > K\) (for some \(K\)) when the null hypothesis is true (\(p=0.5\)) and when it is false (\(p=0.6\)). We see that if the null hypothesis is true, the probability to reject (red region) is quite small. When the null hypothesis is false, that probability is much larger.

Now, this procedure can lead to two types of mistakes:

  • type I error: null hypothesis is true, but you reject it.
  • type II error: null hypothesis is not true, but you fail to reject it.

The probability of making a type I error is called the level of significance of the test and it is often denoted with the Greek letter \(\alpha\). It is sometimes even referred to as the \(\alpha\) level.

7.1.0.4 Exercise

Suppose we toss a coin 250 times and observe \(X\) heads. We reject the null hypothesis if \(|X-125|>K\).

  1. Use \({\tt pbinom}\) to determine the level of significance when \(K=5\), \(K=10\) and \(K=20\).

  2. Use simulation to determine the level of significance when \(K=5\), \(K=10\) and \(K=20\).

Click for the answer
  1. We have to compute the probability that we reject H0 (p=1/2) when it is true.
K=5
pbinom(125-K-1,250,1/2) + 1 - pbinom(125+K,250,1/2)
## [1] 0.4866918
  1. Now use simulation. We approximate a probability with a frequency.
reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
  x=rbinom(1,250,1/2)
  reject=reject + (abs(x-125) > K)
}
reject/10000
## [1] 0.4906
You can do K=10 and K=20 yourself!

\(~\)

Of course, we would like the probability of committing either error to be zero, but this is usually not possible – you can never exclude bad luck! However, we do have some control over the two types of error. By increasing \(K\), we can decrease the chance of a type I error. Unfortunately, this is at the expense of increasing the chance of a type II error.

Analogy Think of a fire alarm. If it is too sensitive, it goes off whenever you use the toaster. If it is too insensitive (after you get annoyed and take out the battery), the house might burn down without the alarm going off.

7.1.0.5 Exercise

True or false: probability of a type I error = (1 \(-\) probability of a type II error).

Click for the answer

This is absolutely not true!

  • probability of a type I error = probability of rejecting H_0 when it is true.
  • probability of a type II error = 1 - probability of rejecting H_0 when it is false.
\(~\) So the type I and II errors are about different situations; what happens when H0 is true versus what happens when it is false.

\(~\)

Our choice for the cut-off \(K\) should really depend on the consequences of making a type I error or a type II error. However, in many situations, the scientific community simply insists that the probability of a type I error (level of significance) must not exceed 0.05.

7.1.0.6 Exercise

Suppose all statistical tests are done at the 5% level. Does that imply that not more than 5% of all significant results are false positives?

Click for the answer

No! Consider two conditional probabilities

  • P( reject H0 | H0 is true) versus
  • P(H0 is true | reject H0)

By testing at the 5% level, we ensure that the first probability is not more than 5%. But this says nothing about the second probability.

\(~\) In general, P(A | B) and P(B | A) are very different things! For example, think of A = person is female and B = person has breast cancer. Then P(A | B) is very large, but - fortunately - P(B | A) not.

\(~\)

7.1.0.7 Exercise

In our coin tossing experiment, use \({\tt pbinom}\) to determine the smallest \(K\) such that the level of significance does not exceed \(\alpha=0.05\). Repeat the Exercise for \(\alpha=0.01\) and \(\alpha=0.1\).

Click for the answer

Here is a rather silly way; just check all the possible cut-offs

}

So, the smallest value for K such that the level of significance does not exceed 5% is K=15.

\(~\)

Trying out different values for \(K\) to determine the appropriate critical value is not the most practical way. We want to find the smallest \(K\) such that \[P({\rm reject}\ H_0) = P(|X - 125| > K) \leq 0.05\] when the null hypothesis (\(p=1/2\)) is true. The distribution of the test statistic \(|X-125|\) under the null hypothesis is not easy. But we can use simulation!

x=rbinom(10^6,250,1/2)
t=abs(x-125)
hist(t,100,main="distribution of T=|X-125| under H0")

Now, we can find \(K\) as follows:

t=sort(t)
K=t[950000]
K
## [1] 15

R has a built-in function that makes this even easier:

quantile(t,0.95)
## 95% 
##  15

7.1.0.9 Exercise

Why should we use the smallest \(K\) such that the level of significance does not exceed a given level of significance?

Click for the answer If we take a larger K, we still guarantee a valid test (level of significance (chance of a type I error) does not exceed alpha, but we needlessly increase the chance of a type II error.

\(~\)

7.1.0.10 Exercise

On the basis of the Polish experiment, do you reject the null hypothesis that the coin is fair at level of significance \(\alpha=0.05\)? Do you reject it at level \(\alpha=0.01\)? Do you reject it at level \(\alpha=0.1\)?

Click for the answer

We reject at level 0.05 if |X-125|>15. In the Polish experiment we have |140-125|=15 so we do not reject at level 0.05.

  • We reject at level 0.01 if |X-125|>20. So we do not reject at level 0.01.
  • We reject at level 0.1 if |X-125|>13. So we do reject at level 0.1.

7.2 One and two-sided tests

We will now discuss the difference between one- and two-sided tests. Suppose we are not interested if the probability of heads is unequal to 1/2, but we want to know specifically if it is greater than 1/2. So, we want to test \[H_0: p\leq 1/2 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: p > 1/2.\] This is called a one-sided test. It makes sense to reject \(H_0\) only if we get more than 125 heads. So, now we reject \(H_0\) if \[X > K.\]

7.2.0.1 Exercise

In our coin tossing experiment, determine the smallest \(K\) such that the level of significance does not exceed \(\alpha=0.05\). Do you reject the null hypothesis?

Click for the answer

Now we reject H_0 if X>K. We need to find the smallest K such that the probability of rejecting H_0 when it is true (so p=1/2) does not exceed 0.05.

We can try out different values for K

for (K in 125:140){
   alpha=1 - pbinom(K,250,1/2)  # probability to reject
                                # H0 when H0 is true
   cat(K,alpha,'\n')
}
## 125 0.4747939 
## 126 0.4247818 
## 127 0.375951 
## 128 0.3290278 
## 129 0.2846507 
## 130 0.2433459 
## 131 0.2055095 
## 132 0.1713993 
## 133 0.1411362 
## 134 0.1147124 
## 135 0.09200755 
## 136 0.07280858 
## 137 0.05683279 
## 138 0.04375117 
## 139 0.03321058 
## 140 0.02485339

We find K is 138. It is much easier to use simulation

x=rbinom(10^6,250,p=1/2)
quantile(x,0.95)
## 95% 
## 138

The test statistic for the one-sided test is just the number of successes \(X\). When the null hypothesis is true, the distribution of \(X\) is very easy. It’s binomial with \(n=250\) and \(p=1/2\). That means we do not need to try out different values for \(K\), and we also do not need to use simulation. We can use the quantile function of the binomial to determine the critical value:

qbinom(0.95,250,0.5)
## [1] 138

In a medical context, tests are almost always two-sided. This may seems strange if you are only interested in showing that your drug is better than placebo, not worse. On the other hand, it’s just a convention.

We end this section with some food for thought. We have seen that by the usual standards of scientific rigour the Polish data do not show a statistically significant deviation from fairness. But to evaluate the evidence for or against a particular claim, there is much more to consider than statistical significance.

First of all, the physical mechanics of flipping a coin in the air imply that it must be very close to fair, even if the coin is not symmetric.

However, spinning a coin on the table is a different story. It is typically not fair to spin a coin. Whether the coin lands heads or tails depends very much on the shape of the edge of the coin. You can make a very unfair coin by filing the rim a little! Magician and probability professor Persi Diaconis discusses these things here.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AYnJv68T3MM

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9RKKoXw7wJw

From a statistical point of view the Polish “experiment” has many holes. First of all, suppose they did manage to prove that a particular Belgian coin is unfair. Does that prove anything about Belgian coins in general?

Moreover, we know that the experimenters tried a Polish coin first, and it did not look unfair. How many more coins did they try before finding their favorite Belgian coin?

And did they decide on 250 tosses beforehand, or did they stop when the data looked “interesting”? You can see that there are many ways to cheat, or maybe just fool yourself.

7.3 Power

In statistical hypothesis testing we control the probability of a type I error to not exceed some predefined level \(\alpha\). So, if the null hypothesis is true, then the chance of rejecting it is not more than \(\alpha\). Of course, we also want to know how good the test is at detecting a false null hypothesis.

Define the power function of a test as the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis, as a function of the parameter \(p\). So \[\text{power}(p)=P_{p}(\text{reject }H_0).\] In the coin tossing experiment, we reject the null hypothesis at level \(\alpha=0.05\) if \(|X-125| > 15\). The power is \[\begin{align*} \text{power}(p) & = P_{p}(|X-125|>15) \\ &= P_p(X < 110) + P_p(X > 140) \\ &={\tt pbinom(109,250,p)+1-pbinom(140,250,p)} \end{align*}\] Note that this probability is computed assuming the Binomial distribution with \(n=250\) and varying \(p\). We plot the power function and add a horizontal line at 0.05.

7.3.0.1 Exercise

Reproduce the power plot. You can use \({\tt abline(h=0.05)}\) to add a straight line to the plot.

Click for the answer 
p=seq(0,1,0.01)
power=pbinom(109,250,p)+1-pbinom(140,250,p)
plot(p,power,ylab='power = probability to reject H0',type='l',ylim=c(0,1))
abline(0.05,0)

\(~\)

In the Figure, we see that the probability to reject \(H_0\) dips just below 0.05 when \(p=1/2\). We designed our test that way! The probability of rejecting the null hypothesis must be below 0.05 when it is actually true. However, for all other values of \(p\) (when the null hypothesis is not true), we want to reject \(H_0\), so the power should be large. Of course, small deviations from the null hypothesis are difficult to detect. If \(p=0.51\) then we have very little power. On the other hand, if \(p=0.7\) then we have almost 100% power.

7.3.0.2 Exercise

Use \({\tt pbinom}\) to compute the power to detect \(p=0.51\) and \(p=0.7\). Also, use simulation to compute the power approximately.

Click for the answer

power
## [1] 0.06118538
p=0.7

power
## [1] 0.999998
# now use simulation
p=0.51
x=rbinom(10^6,250,p)

## [1] 0.060984
p=0.7
x=rbinom(10^6,250,p)
t=abs(x-125)  # test statistic
mean(t>15)
## [1] 1

\(~\)

7.3.0.3 Exercise

Suppose we perform a one-sided test, and reject the null hypothesis if \(X > 138\). Use \({\tt lines(...,col='red')}\) to plot the power function of this test on top of the power function you plotted before. Think about what you see.

power=1-pbinom(138,250,p)  # power of the one-sided test
lines(p,power,col='red')

\(~\)

A test is designed to have good power against certain alternatives. The one-sided test is good at detecting if the probability of heads is greater than 1/2, but it is not good at detecting if it is less than 1/2.

# a/b

reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
  x=rbinom(1,10,0.5)    # p=0.5, so H0 is true
  reject = reject + (x==0 | x==10)
}
                        # this is the type I error prob

## [1] 0.0025
# c.

reject=0

  reject = reject + (x==0 | x==10)
}
reject/10000            # this is the power
## [1] 0.0299
1 - reject/10000        # this is the type II error prob
## [1] 0.9701

\(~\)

7.3.0.6 Exercise

Suppose we throw a die 102 times and get 23 sixes. This seems a little bit suspicious, because we would expect only 102/6=17 sixes. We decide to test if the die is fair.

  1. Formulate the appropriate null hypothesis and alternative.
  2. Which test statistic do you use to test the null hypothesis?
  3. Suppose we want to test at level \(\alpha=0.05\) what is the critical value for your test statistic?
  4. Do you reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance?
  5. What is the power of the test if the probability of throwing a six is in fact 1/5?
  6. Plot the power function.
Click for the answer

If you suspect that the die is loaded specifically to produce too many sizes, then you might want to do a one-sided test. The answers below are all for the two-sided test.

  1. H0 : p=1/6 versus A : p is not 1/6

  2. If X is the number of sixes, then we use |X - 17| as our test statistic (note that 102/6=17). We reject H_0 when this exceeds some K.

  3. To find the appropriate ciritcal value, let’s try tem out:

for (K in 0:10){
   alpha=pbinom(17-K-1,102,1/6) + 1 - pbinom(17+K,102,1/6)
   cat(K,alpha,'\n')
}

## 1 0.6907131

We see that K=7 is the smallest such that the level of significance does not exceed 5%.

  1. Since we got 23 sixes, we have |17-23|=6 and so we do not reject.

  2. The power to detect p=1/5 is:

K=7
power=pbinom(17-K-1,102,1/5) + 1 - pbinom(17+K,102,1/5)  # power =  0.15

p=seq(0,1,0.01)

abline(v=1/5)   # here's the alternative p=1/5

\(~\)

In the previous exercise, you computed the power to detect that the probability of throwing a six with a loaded die is \(1/5\). This power is quite low. This makes sense, because the difference between 1/6 and 1/5 is not very great.

If we want more power, we can increase the level of significance. That means we “allow” more type I errors to bring down the type II errors.

  2. Get a bigger sample size
