7.4 Normal approximation

We have seen how we can perform a statistical test of an hypothesis about the probability of success in a binomial experiment. It is not difficult to do the calculations using \({\tt dbinom}\) and \({\tt pbinom}\). However, we will now discuss an approximation that is used very often in practice.

If the sample size \(n\) is large, and the probability \(p\) not too close to zero or one, then the binomial distribution with parameters \(n\) and \(p\) is well approximated by the normal distribution with the same mean and variance. Recall that the binomial distribution has mean \(np\) and variance \(np(1-p)\).

7.4.0.1 Exercise

Don’t take my word for it! Use the code below to try it out for different \(n\) and \(p\). What happens when \(n\) is small? And when \(p\) is close to zero or 1?

Click for the answer 
n=250; 
p=0.5; 
x=0:n
plot(x,dbinom(x,n,p),type="s",ylab='')

x=seq(0,n,0.01)
lines(x,dnorm(x,n*p,sqrt(n*p*(1-p))),col='red')

When n is small or p is close to 0 or 1, you can see that the normal approximation is not good. For example,

n=10; 
p=0.1; 
x=-3:n
plot(x,dbinom(x,n,p),type="s",ylab='',xlim=c(-3,10),ylim=c(0,0.5))
x=seq(-3,n,0.01)
lines(x,dnorm(x,n*p,sqrt(n*p*(1-p))),col='red')

\(~\)

Now recall the Polish coin tossing experiment. If the null hypothesis is true (\(p=1/2\)), then the number of heads (approximately) has the normal distribution with mean \(125\) and variance \(250 \cdot \frac12 \cdot (1-\frac12)=62.5\). So, if the null distribution is true, then \[Z=\frac{X - 125}{\sqrt{62.5}}\] (approximately) has the standard normal distribution (with mean=0 and standard deviation=1). We reject the null distribution if \(|Z|\) exceeds some threshold \(K\). We need to determine \(K\) such that the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is true does not exceed \(\alpha=0.05\). We can use the quantile function of the normal distribution which in \({\tt R}\) is called \({\tt qnorm}\).

K=qnorm(0.975,0,1)
K
## [1] 1.959964

In other words, we can approximately do the hypothesis at level 5% (two-sided) by rejecting when \(|Z|>1.96\).

7.4.0.2 Exercise

Make sure you understand that the quantile function \({\tt qnorm}\) and the cumulative distribution function \({\tt pnorm}\) are each others inverse.

Click for the answer

With the cumulative distribution function, we choose a number and get the probability of drawing less than that number. For example, if X is standard normal, then P(X < 1.96)=0.975

pnorm(1.96,0,1)
## [1] 0.9750021

With the quantile function, we input some probability (number between 0 and 1) and get the number back:

qnorm(0.975,0,1)
## [1] 1.959964
So, the CDF (such as pnorm) and the quantile function (such as qnorm) are each other’s inverse.

\(~\)

7.4.0.3 Exercise

Compute the \(Z\) statistic for the Polish data. Do you reject the null hypothesis at level \(\alpha=0.05\)? Do you reject it at \(\alpha=0.1\)?

Click for the answer

\(Z=(140 - 125)/\sqrt{62.5}=1.9\). Since 1.9 is less than 1.96, we do not reject the null hypothesis at alpha=0.05.

\(~\)

To test at level alpha=0.1, we must compare |Z| with qnorm(0.95,0,1)=1.64. Since 1.9 is greater than 1.64 we reject the null hypothesis at level alpha=0.1.

\(~\)

7.5 What have we learned: hypothesis testing

Suppose we have an independent sample \(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n\) from some probability distribution. Hypothesis testing is a decision problem: We have to decide if our probability distribution is among a set of probability distributions \(H_0\) (null hypothesis) or a set of probability distributions \(H_1\) (alternative hypothesis). The null hypothesis \(H_0\) gets the benefit of doubt; we reject it only if it is very unlikely that any distribution from \(H_0\) could have produced our data.

We formalize this as follows. Specify some event \(R\) that is unlikely to happen if \(H_0\) is true, and then reject \(H_0\) if \(R\) does occur. The event \(R\) almost always has the form of a test statistic exceeding some critical value.

If \(H_0\) is true and \(R\) occurs, we make a type I error. The probability of a type I error is called the level of significance or \(\alpha\) for short. Typically, we choose \(R\) in such a way that \(\alpha\) does not exceed 0.05.

If \(H_0\) is not true and \(R\) does not occur, then we make a type II error.

The power of a test at particular probability distribution, is the probability of \(R\) under that probability distribution. The power must not exceed \(\alpha\) for distributions in \(H_0\), while a good test has large power at distributions in \(H_1\).

So, to test some null hypothesis at significance level \(\alpha\), we can follow this recipe:

  1. Choose a test statistic \(T\), which a random variable (a function of the data) that you expect to have large values if the null hypothesis is false, and small values if the null hypothesis is true.
  2. Find the distribution of \(T\) when the null hypothesis is true. You can do this either analytically or by simulation.
  3. Find the critical value \(t_\alpha\), which is the \((1-\alpha)\)-quantile of the distribution of \(T\) under the null hypothesis.
  4. If the observed \(T\) is larger than the critical value \(t_\alpha\), reject the null hypothesis.

8 Confidence intervals

8.1 Some familiar and some unfamiliar tests

We have discussed the normal approximation to the binomial test of a proportion. There is also a normal approximation to the test for a difference of two proportions. This approximation is called the chi-squared test, or \(\chi^2\) test

Consider, the following situation. A Belgian euro is tossed 250 times and 140 heads are obtained. Then a Dutch euro is tossed 20 times and 7 heads are obtained. Is there a significant difference between the probability of heads of the two coins at level \(\alpha=0.05\)? We start by construct a 2x2 contingency table:

Observed = matrix(c(140,110,7,13),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Observed
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]  140  110
## [2,]    7   13

If the probability of heads is the same in both experiments, then we would estimate it as \(\hat p = 147/270\). With this estimate, we can compute the expected table if both probabilities were the same.

Expected = matrix(c(136.1,113.9,10.9,9.1),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Expected
##       [,1]  [,2]
## [1,] 136.1 113.9
## [2,]  10.9   9.1

Now we compute a test statistic that becomes large when the expected table differs from the observed table. \[X^2 = \sum_{i=1}^4 \frac{(O_i - E_i)^2}{E_i} = \frac{(140-136.1)^2}{136.1} + \frac{(110 - 113.9)^2}{113.9} + \frac{(7-10.9)^2}{10.9} + \frac{(13-9.1)^2}{9.1}=3.3\]

In R, we can do

X2=sum((Observed - Expected)^2/Expected)
X2
## [1] 3.312136

Under \(H_0\) our test statistic \(X^2\) has the chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom. Here’s the density of this distribution

x=seq(0,4,0.01)
plot(x,dchisq(x,1),type="l")

The critical value for testing at level \(\alpha=0.05\) is

qchisq(0.95,1)
## [1] 3.841459

Since X2=3.3 is less than qchisq(0.95,1)=3.8, we do NOT reject \(H_0\) at \(\alpha=0.05\).

8.1.0.1 Exercise

Suppose that 160 patients are divided randomly into two groups of 80. The patients in the first group are given some treatment, and 30 of the 80 recover from their illness. In the other group, the patients are given a placebo, and only 20 recover. So, we have the following 2x2 table

Observed = matrix(c(30,50,20,60),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Observed
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   30   50
## [2,]   20   60

Test the hypothesis that there is no difference between the treatment and placebo at 5% level of significance. Also, test at 10% level of significance.

Click for the answer

Under the null hypothesis (no difference) we estimate the probability of recovery at p=50/160. So, the 2x2 table of expected counts is

p=50/160
Expected = matrix(c(80*p,80*(1-p),80*p,80*(1-p)),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Expected
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   25   55
## [2,]   25   55

The chi-squared statistic is

X2=sum((Observed - Expected)^2/Expected)
X2
## [1] 2.909091

The critical value for testing at level 5% is

qchisq(0.95,1)
## [1] 3.841459

Since X2=2.9 is less than qchisq(0.9,1)=3.8, we do NOT reject the null at alpha=5%.

\(~\)

The critical value for testing at level 10% is

qchisq(0.9,1)
## [1] 2.705543

Since X2=2.9 is greater than qchisq(0.9,1)=2.7, we reject the null at alpha=10%.

\(~\)

The \(\chi^2\) test extends easily to tables with \(n\) rows and \(m\) columns, but we shall not discuss that here.

8.1.1 \(Z\) test for the mean

Suppose we have an iid sample from a normal distribution with unknown mean \(\mu\) and known variance \(\sigma^2\). We want to test \[H_0 : \mu = \mu_0 \quad \text{versus}\quad A : \mu \neq \mu_0\] at level \(\alpha\) for some fixed value \(\mu_0\). We can base our test on \[Z = \frac{\bar X - \mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}.\] If \(H_0\) is true, then \(Z\) has the standard normal distribution. So, to test at level \(\alpha\), we may compare \(Z\) to the \((1-\alpha/2) \times 100\%\) quantile of the standard normal distribution.

8.1.1.1 Exercise

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find 983, 1041, 1026, 1025, 1033, 968 and 1028 (grams). We know that the standard deviation of the weight is 25 grams. We want to test \[H_0 : \mu = 1000 \quad \text{versus}\quad A : \mu \neq 1000\] at level \(\alpha=0.05\).

  1. Compute the \(Z\) statistic.
  2. What is the critical value for your test statistic?
  3. Do you reject the null hypothesis?
  4. What is the power when true mean weight is actually 980 grams?
  5. Plot the power function.
Click for the answer 
x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)
z=sqrt(7)*(mean(x)-1000)/25    # z statistic
z
## [1] 1.572332
  1. So far, we determined the critical value K by trial-and-error. Here we use the quantile function:

\(~\) If H0 is true, then Z has the standard normal distribution.

  • If |Z| < K then we do not reject
  • So, we want P(|Z| < K)=0.95, when Z has the standard normal distribution.
  • So, we want P(Z < K)=0.975, when Z has the standard normal distribution.
  • So, K=qnorm(0.975,0,1)
K=qnorm(0.975,0,1) 
K
## [1] 1.959964

  1. Since |z|=1.57 is less than K=qnorm(0.975,0,1)=1.96, we do NOT reject.

  2. We reject if |Z| > K where Z = sqrt(7) * (Xbar - 1000)/25. To compute the power, we need to know the probability that this happens when mu=980. Note: \[ \begin{align*} Z &= \sqrt{7}\frac{\bar X - 1000}{25} \\ &= \sqrt{7}\frac{\bar X - 980}{25} + \sqrt{7}\frac{-20}{25} \\ &= \sqrt{7}\frac{\bar X - 980}{25} - 2.12 \end{align*} \] So, if mu=980, then Z has the normal distribution with mean -2.12 and standard deviation 1. The probability that |Z|>1.96 becomes

power=pnorm(-1.96,-2.12,1) + (1 - pnorm(1.96,-2.12,1))
power
## [1] 0.563582

To plot the power

mu=950:1050                       # mean of X
meanZ = sqrt(7) * (mu - 1000)/25  # mean of Z

power=pnorm(-1.96,meanZ,1) + (1 - pnorm(1.96,meanZ,1))
plot(mu,power,type='l',ylim=c(0,1))
abline(h=0.05)

\(~\)

Repeat part d. of the previous Exercise, but now use simulation.

Now, we have long suspected that the supermarket is cheating by putting on average less than 1 kilo in their bags. We want to do a one-sided test at level \(\alpha=0.05\). Formulate the appropriate null hypothesis and alternative, find the critical value and plot the power function.

Click for the answer

x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)

Z

Notice the minus sign! We reject when z is large. The critical value is

qnorm(0.95,0,1)
## [1] 1.644854

We reject if Z > 1.64 where Z = - sqrt(7) * (Xbar - 1000)/25. To compute the power curve, we need to know the probability that this happens. For any \(\mu\): \[ \begin{align*} Z &= - \sqrt{7} \frac{\bar X - 1000}{25} \\ &= - \sqrt{7} \frac{\bar X - \mu}{25} - \sqrt{7} \frac{\mu-1000}{25} \end{align*} \] To plot the power

mu=950:1050                       # mean of X
meanZ = - sqrt(7) * (mu - 1000)/25  # mean of Z

power=(1 - pnorm(1.64,meanZ,1))
plot(mu,power,type='l',ylim=c(0,1))
abline(h=0.05)

8.1.2 \(t\) test for the mean

The \(Z\) test of the previous paragraph is almost never used in practice, because one typically does not know the variance. If the variance is not known, then it must be estimated on the basis of the data. We can base our test on \[T = \frac{\bar X - \mu_0}{S/\sqrt{n}},\] where \(S\) i the sample standard deviation.

If \(H_0\) is true, then \(T\) has the \(t\) distribution with \(n-1\) degrees of freedom. So, to test at level \(\alpha\), we may compare \(|T|\) to the \((1-\alpha/2) \times 100\%\) quantile of the \(t\) distribution with \(n-1\) degrees of freedom.

By using the \(t\) distribution instead of the standard normal, we account for the uncertainty that comes from not knowing \(\sigma\). If we plot the standard normal and a few \(t\) distributions (with varying degrees of freedom), we notice that the \(t\) distribution is wider than the standard normal reflecting this extra uncertainty. The difference disappears as the sample size (degrees of freedom) increases. This makes sense, because for large sample sizes \(S\) becomes a very precise estimate of \(\sigma\) and \(T\) and \(Z\) become almost equal.

8.1.2.1 Exercise

In the same figure, plot the standard normal and a few \(t\) distributions with varying degrees of freedom.

Click for the answer 
x=seq(-4,4,0.01)
plot(x,dnorm(x,0,1),type='l',ylab='')
lines(x,dt(x,5),col='blue')          #  5 degrees of freedom
lines(x,dt(x,10),col='red')          # 10 degrees of freedom
lines(x,dt(x,50),col='green')        # 50 degrees of freedom

\(~\)

8.1.2.2 Exercise

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find 983, 1041, 1026, 1025, 1033, 968 and 1028 (grams). Suppose that we do not know the standard deviation of the weight. We want to test \[H_0 : \mu = 1000 \quad \text{versus}\quad A : \mu \neq 1000\] at level \(\alpha=0.05\).

  1. Compute the \(t\) statistic.
  2. What is the critical value for your test statistic?
  3. Do you reject the null hypothesis?
  4. Use simulation to compute the power when true mean weight is actually 980 grams?

If H0 is true, then t has the t distribution with n-1=6 degrees of freedom. - If |t| < K then we do not reject - So, we want P(|t| < K)=0.95, when t distribution with n-1=6 degrees of freedom. - So, we want P(t < K)=0.975, when t distribution with n-1=6 degrees of freedom. - So, K=qt(0.975,6)

K=qt(0.975,6) 
K
## [1] 2.446912

  1. Since |t|=1.42 is less than K=qt(0.975,6)=2.45, we do NOT reject.

s=sd(x)
reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
  x=rnorm(7,980,s)                   # use the estimated sd
  t=sqrt(7)*(mean(x) - 1000)/sd(x)   # estimate the sd of the simulated data
  reject = reject + (abs(t) > 2.45)
}
reject/10000                         # power
## [1] 0.3657

8.1.3 \(t\) test for difference of two means

We have used the \(t\) test to test if the mean is equal to some fixed value. The \(t\) test can also be used to test if the means of two populations differ.

Suppose we have a new drug that aims to lower blood pressure. Suppose that we have 35 patients with high blood pressure. We randomly select 20 patients to receive tablets to lower their blood pressure. The remaining 15 patients receive a placebo (inert tablets). Neither the patients nor the doctors know which patients receive the drug.

8.1.3.1 Exercise

What is the purpose of

  1. having a control group (the 15 patients)?
  2. giving the controls placebo?
  3. blinding the patients?
  4. blinding the physician?
Click for the answer

  1. Perhaps everybody gets better or worse in time, if you give the medication or not. The controls allow us to compare to what happens if we do nothing.

  2. We want to account for the psycho-somatic effect that giving any pill will make patients feel better.

  3. We blind the patients because if patients know they got placebo, they will automatically feel worse.

  4. We blind the physician because otherwise (consciously or sub-consciously) the physician might influence the patients.

\(~\)

Let us generate a fake data set of measurements after two weeks of treatment. We arrange it so that there is indeed a difference between the two groups in the mean blood pressure.

set.seed(123)
x = rnorm(20,140,3)  #20 patients with mean 140 mmHg systolic and standard deviation 3
y = rnorm(15,142,3)  #15 controls with mean 142 mmHg systolic and standard deviation 3

We can compare the two groups using a boxplot.

boxplot(list(x,y))

Boxplots are quite useful for a quick look. They show the median and the 25% en 75% quantiles as a box''. Thewhiskers’’ show the most extreme values. Essentially, \({\tt boxplot(x)}\) conveys the same information as \({\tt summary(x)}\).

Formally, we have the following problem. Suppose \(X_1,X_2,...,X_n\) are normally distributed with mean \(\mu_X\) and unknown variance \(\sigma^2\). Suppose \(Y_1,Y_2,...,Y_m\) are normally distributed with mean \(\mu_X\) and the same, but unknown variance \(\sigma^2\). We want to test

\[H_0 : \mu_X=\mu_Y\quad {\rm versus}\quad A: \mu_X \neq \mu_Y.\]

We use as our test statistic \[T = \frac{\bar X - \bar Y}{S_p\sqrt{\frac1n + \frac1m}},\] where \[S_p^2 = \frac{(n-1)S^2_X + (m-1)S^2_Y}{m+n-2},\] with \[S^2_X = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \bar X)^2\quad{\rm and}\quad S^2_Y = \frac{1}{m-1}\sum_{i=1}^m (Y_i - \bar Y)^2.\] Under the null hypothesis, \(T\) has the \(t\) distribution with \(n+m-2\) degrees of freedom. We choose some critical value \(K\) and reject the null hypothesis if \(|T|\) exceeds \(K\).

8.1.3.2 Exercise

Use the data you generated above. Suppose we want to test at level \(\alpha=0.05\). Use \({\tt qt}\) to determine the critical value \(K\) and carry out the test.

Click for the answer 
set.seed(123)
x = rnorm(20,140,3)  #20 patients with mean 140 mmHg systolic and standard deviation 3
y = rnorm(15,142,3)  #15 controls with mean 142 mmHg systolic and standard deviation 3
n=length(x)
m=length(y)
S2x=var(x)
S2y=var(y)
S2p=((n-1)*S2x + (m-1)*S2y)/(n+m-2)
t=(mean(x) - mean(y))/(sqrt(S2p)*sqrt(1/n + 1/m))
t
## [1] -1.302519

compare to

K=qt(0.975,n+m-2)
K
## [1] 2.034515

Since |t|=1.3 is less than K=2.0 we do not reject.

\(~\)

8.1.3.3 Exercise

Carry out the test a few times with different \(n,m,\mu_1,\mu_2\) and \(\sigma^2\) making boxplots each time you generate a new data set.

Click for the answer The point is that the t.test compares the difference between the groups to the differences within the groups.

\(~\)

Again, generate data by

y = rnorm(15,142,3)

Since t=-1.3 is larger than qt(0.05,n+m-2)=-1.69, we do not reject.

8.1.4 Unfamiliar tests

The chi-squared test, \(z\)-test and \(t\)-test are very often used in practice. But the principle of hypothesis testing is much more general and can be applied in many different situations. Now, let’s consider some unfamiliar tests.

8.1.4.1 Exercise

Suppose we have a sample of size \(n = 5\) from the normal distribution with mean \(\mu = 0\) and unknown standard deviation \(\sigma\). Suppose we decide to test \[H_0 : \sigma = 2 \quad {\rm versus}\quad A: \sigma > 2.\]

by computing the sample standard deviation \(S\), and rejecting \(H_0\) if \(S\) is greater than 2. Use simulation to answer the following questions.

  1. What is the level of significance of this test.
  2. What is the power of the test against the alternative \(\sigma = 3\)?
  3. Use trial-and-error to find the critical value so that the test has level 5%.
  4. An alternative approach to trial-and-error is as follows. Simulate the test statistic many times under the null hypothesis. Then use the R function quantile to get the value which is exceeded by 95% of the sample.
Click for the answer 
# a.
reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rnorm(5,0,2)
reject=reject + (sd(x)>2)
}
reject/10000 # 0.40 (approximately)
## [1] 0.4079
# b.
reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rnorm(5,0,3)
reject=reject + (sd(x)>2)
}
reject/10000 # 0.77 (approximately)
## [1] 0.7705
# c.
reject=0
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rnorm(5,0,2)
reject=reject + (sd(x)>3.08)
}
reject/10000 # 0.05 (approximately)
## [1] 0.0494
# d
stat=rep(0,10000)
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rnorm(5,0,2)
stat[i]=sd(x)
}
quantile(stat,probs=0.95)
##      95% 
## 3.104163

\(~\)

8.1.4.2 Exercise

Suppose we have a random sample of size \(n\) = 12 and want to test the (null) hypothesis that they were drawn from the normal distribution with mean 1 and standard deviation 1 versus the alternative that they were drawn from the exponential distribution with mean 1. We know that the normal distribution is symmetric, so that the (population) mean and de median are equal. The exponential distribtuion, however, is skewed to the right so that the mean is larger than the median. So, we decide to use the following test: Compute the sample mean \(\bar x\) and the sample median \(m\), and reject the null hypothesis if \(\bar x - m > 0.3\).

You should use simulation to answer the following questions. You can use the R functions \({\tt median}\) to compute the median and \({\tt rnorm}\) and \({\tt rexp}\) to generate random samples.

  1. What is the significance level of the test?
  2. What is the probability of a type II error?
  3. What is the power against the alternative?
  4. Below are the 12 random numbers, rounded to two decimals. Do you reject the null hypothesis?
x=c(1.01, 2.87, 0.93, 0.52, 0.61, 3.37, 2.07, 0.62, 0.72, 0.52, 1.31, 0.91)
Click for the answer

Note that N(1,1) and Exp(1) have the same mean and variance. However, the exponential distribution is more skewed than the normal and this should be noticeable as a difference between the mean and the median. If you’re interested, the median of N(1,1) is 1 (equal to the mean) and the median of Exp(1) is log(2)=0.69.

# a.
count=0
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rnorm(12,1,1)
count = count + (mean(x)-median(x) > 0.3)
}
count/10000 # about 0.05
## [1] 0.0516
#
# b.
count=0
for (i in 1:10000){
x=rexp(12,1)
count = count + (mean(x)-median(x) < 0.3) # fail to reject
}
count/10000 # about 0.61
## [1] 0.6166

  1. The power is one minus the probability of a type II error

x=c(1.01, 2.87, 0.93, 0.52, 0.61, 3.37, 2.07, 0.62, 0.72, 0.52, 1.31, 0.91)
mean(x) - median(x) # 0.368 which is larger than 0.3, so reject.
## [1] 0.3683333

\(~\)

8.2 Confidence interval

A confidence interval is a set of parameter values that are compatible with the data to some degree. We can formalize this rather vague notion by using hypothesis tests.

Consider the coin tossing example again, where we can test \[H_0 : p=p_0\quad {\rm versus}\quad A: p \neq p_0.\]

at some level \(\alpha\). We have done the test for \(p_0=1/2\), but we can do it for any value of \(p_0\) between 0 and 1: \[\begin{align*} &H_0 : p=0.01 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: p \neq 0.01 \\ &H_0 : p=0.02 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: p \neq 0.02 \\ &H_0 : p=0.03 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: p \neq 0.03 \\ &\dots \\ &H_0 : p=0.99 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: p \neq 0.99 \\ \end{align*}\]

If we do all these tests, then we can list the ones that we do not reject. That is called a \((1 - \alpha ) \times 100\%\) confidence interval.

Recall that we got 140 heads out of 250 tosses, We will use the normal approximation for the binomial test to make the computations easy.

x=140
n=250
p0=seq(0.05,0.95,0.05)
z=(x - n*p0)/sqrt(n*p0*(1-p0))
reject=abs(z)>1.96
cbind(p0,z,reject)
##         p0           z reject
##  [1,] 0.05  36.9992888      1
##  [2,] 0.10  24.2441287      1
##  [3,] 0.15  18.1551052      1
##  [4,] 0.20  14.2302495      1
##  [5,] 0.25  11.3195995      1
##  [6,] 0.30   8.9708523      1
##  [7,] 0.35   6.9614322      1
##  [8,] 0.40   5.1639778      1
##  [9,] 0.45   3.4960295      1
## [10,] 0.50   1.8973666      0
## [11,] 0.55   0.3178209      0
## [12,] 0.60  -1.2909944      0
## [13,] 0.65  -2.9834709      1
## [14,] 0.70  -4.8304589      1
## [15,] 0.75  -6.9378191      1
## [16,] 0.80  -9.4868330      1
## [17,] 0.85 -12.8414158      1
## [18,] 0.90 -17.9195734      1
## [19,] 0.95 -28.2935738      1

We get a very rough indication of the confidence interval. It runs from about 0.5 to 0.6. We can get a more precise result if we make the step size smaller.

8.2.0.2 Exercise

Repeat the previous Exercise, but change the level of significance to see what happens.
Click for the answer

If you increase the level of significance (say to 10%) the confidence interval becomes more narrow. Now you allow 10% probability to “miss” the true value.

If you decrease the level of significance (say to 1%) the confidence interval becomes more wide. Now you allow only 1% probability to “miss” the true value.

\(~\)

The confidence interval is about 0.541 to 0.579. So if we have more data, then the confidence interval becomes more narrow This makes sense; with more data we have more certainty.

\(~\)

Doing all the tests and checking the rejections is not the smartest way to compute a confidence interval. In simple cases, it is much better to use mathematics. So, we do not reject the null hypothesis if \[|Z| = \left| \frac{X - np_0}{\sqrt{np_0(1-p_0)}} \right| < 1.96\] But this is approximately the same as \[|Z| = \left| \frac{X - np_0}{\sqrt{n \hat p(1-\hat p)}} \right| < 1.96\] where \(\hat p = X/n\) is our estimator. Now we can solve for \(p_0\) and find that we do not reject if \[\hat p - 1.96 \sqrt{\hat p(1-\hat p)/n} < p_0 < \hat p + 1.96 \sqrt{\hat p(1-\hat p)/n}\]

8.2.0.4 Exercise

Compute the confidence interval for the Polish experiment using the formula above, and compare to the previous Exercises.

Click for the answer 
x=140
n=250
p=140/250
lower=p - 1.96 * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
lower
## [1] 0.4984672
upper=p + 1.96 * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
upper
## [1] 0.6215328

\(~\)

If you did the previous exercise correctly, you will have found that the value 0.5 is in the 95% confidence interval. This makes perfect sense since the confidence interval consists of all parameter values that are not rejected at the 5% level, and we already know that we do not reject the hypothesis of a fair coin at that level.

\(~\)

8.2.1 Coverage

When we do a test at significance level \(\alpha\), we are making sure that the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is true is not more than \(\alpha\). So, this means that the probability that the confidence interval does not contain the true value is not more than \(\alpha\). In other words, the probability that the confidence interval does contain the true value is at least \(1 - \alpha\). This is then called the coverage probability. Let’s verify this claim.

8.2.1.1 Exercise

Choose some number \(n\) and some probability \(p\). Use \({\tt rbinom}\) to generate a sample \(x\) from the binomial distribution, and construct the 95% confidence interval. Check if the true \(p\) (the one that you used to sample \(X\)) is in the confidence interval. Now repeat 10,000 times and check if this happened about 95% of the time.

Click for the answer 
n=200
p0=0.4  # the true prob of succes

cover=0
for (i in 1:10000){
  x=rbinom(1,n,p0)
  p=x/n
  lower=p - qnorm(0.975) * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
  upper=p + qnorm(0.975) * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
  cover = cover + ((lower < p0) & (upper > p0))
}
cover/10000
## [1] 0.9523

\(~\)

8.2.1.2 Exercise

Repeat the previous exercise with the 90% confidence interval.

Click for the answer 
n=200
p0=0.3  # the true prob of succes

cover=0
for (i in 1:10000){
  x=rbinom(1,n,p0)
  p=x/n
  lower=p - qnorm(0.95) * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
  upper=p + qnorm(0.95) * sqrt(p*(1-p)/n)
  cover = cover + ((lower < p0) & (upper > p0))
}
cover/10000
## [1] 0.909

\(~\)

Coverage is often misunderstood, so it’s very important to understand what it really means. The parameter is unknown, but it is fixed. The confidence interval is what’s random. It “hits” the unknown parameter with probability \(1-\alpha\).

Note that a realized confidence interval is not random anymore. So all we can say is that must have hit or not hit the unknown parameter, but we cannot assign a probability to that.

For example, suppose we have a sample of size \(n=200\) from the binomial distribution with unknown parameter \(p\). Let’s compute 40 95% confidence intervals when \(p=0.3\). We would expect about 2 of those (i.e. 5% of 40) to miss. It’s helpful to think of the following picture

Now, let’s compute some more confidence intervals.

8.2.1.4 Exercise

Show that the 95% confidence interval for the mean \(\mu\) of a normal distribution with known standard deviation \(\sigma\) is given by \[\bar X - 1.96 \sigma/\sqrt{n} < \mu < \bar X + 1.96 \sigma/\sqrt{n}\]

Use the formula to compute the confidence interval, and compare to the previous exercise.

Click for the answer

The confidence interval consists of all values mu0 that are NOT rejected when testing

\(~\)

H0: mu=mu0 versus A: mu is not mu0

\(~\)

Let X.bar be the average of X1,..,Xn, and sigma the (known) standard deviation. We do NOT reject H0 if \(\sqrt{n} |\bar x - \mu_0|/\sigma < 1.96\). Now, solving for mu0 we obtain the confidence interval.

x=c(983, 1041, 1026, 1025, 1033, 968, 1028)
lower = mean(x) - qnorm(0.975)*25/sqrt(7)
lower
## [1] 996.3372
upper = mean(x) + qnorm(0.975)*25/sqrt(7)
upper
## [1] 1033.377

\(~\)

8.2.1.5 Exercise

Give the formula for the 80% confidence interval for the mean \(\mu\) of a normal distribution with known standard deviation \(\sigma\).

Click for the answer

Let X.bar be the average of X1,..,Xn, and sigma the (known) standard deviation. The 80% confidence interval is

lower = X.bar - qnorm(0.9)*sigma/sqrt(n) = X.bar - 1.28*sigma/sqrt(n)
upper = X.bar + qnorm(0.9)*sigma/sqrt(n) = X.bar - 1.28*sigma/sqrt(n)

\(~\)

8.3 What have we learned

  • We know some standard tests, and can apply non-standard tests
  • We know that a confidence interval is a set of parameter values that are compatible with the data to some degree.
  • We know that a confidence interval is a set of parameter values that are not rejected at some particular level of significance.
  • We can compute confidence intervals in standard situations.

\(~\)

9 Tests based on likelihood

We have learned general recipes for performing a hypothesis test based on a tests statistic, but how do we come up with a test statistic? That is what this lecture is about.

9.1 Is any test statistic fine?

All we need to be able to do an hypothesis test is a test-statistic (= a number that can be computed from data) which tends to become large when the true distribution of the data is further from the null hypothesis. In many cases it is obvious which statistic we should use, but in many more cases it is not!

Suppose we have a sample \(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n\) from the normal distribution with mean 0 and unknown variance \(\sigma^2\). We want to test \[H_0: \sigma^2 = 1 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: \sigma^2 > 1.\] As test statistic we can use any measure of variability in the data. Here are just a few:

  • the sample variance \(S^2 = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \bar X)^2\)
  • the MLE \(\hat\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \bar X)^2\)
  • the mean absolute deviation \(\text{MAD} = \frac1n \sum_{i=1}^n |X_i - \bar X|\)
  • the range \(\max(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n) - \min(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n)\)
  • the interquartile range (IQR), which is the difference between the 75% and 25% quantiles.

All of these can be used to construct a hypothesis test. We simply follow the general recipe we learned in the previous lecture. To test some null hypothesis at significance level \(\alpha\) we:

  1. Choose a test statistic \(T\), a random variable that you expect to have large values if the null hypothesis is false, and small values if the null hypothesis is true.
  2. Find the distribution of \(T\) under the null hypothesis, either analytically or by simulation.
  3. Find \(t_\alpha\), the \((1-\alpha)\)-quantile of the distribution of \(T\).
  4. If the observed \(T\) is larger than \(t_\alpha\), reject the null hypothesis.

Of course an \(\alpha\)-level must be chosen as well. If the \(\alpha\)-level is not mentioned in an exercise, use \(\alpha=0.05\).

\(~\)

9.1.0.1 Exercise

Suppose we use the range \(\max(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n) - \min(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n)\) as the test statistic for testing \(H_0: \sigma^2 = 1 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: \sigma^2 > 1\). Suppose also that \(n=6\).

  1. Use simulation to find the critical value for testing at significance level \(\alpha=0.05\).
  2. Suppose we observe \(X = (2.0, 2.9, -0.5, 0.3, -0.8, -0.1)\). Do we reject the null hypothesis?
Click for the answer 
X = c(2.0,  2.9, -0.5,  0.3, -0.8, -0.1)
N <- length(X)
# simulate test statistics under H0
null_statistics <- replicate( 1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, 0, 1)
  diff(range(X))      # same as max(X) - min(X) 
})
critical_value <- quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
critical_value
##      95% 
## 4.023349
observed_statistic <- diff(range(X))
observed_statistic
## [1] 3.7

Since the observed statistic 3.7 does not exceed than the critical value of 4.0 we do not reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

In this recipe, steps 2-4 are relatively straightforward. Given \(T\), we know what to do to obtain its distribution and its quantile. Step 1, in contrast, requires some thinking. What test statistic should we choose? Are some test statistics better than others? What is a good way to choose a test statistic? Those are the question we will discuss in this lecture.

\(~\)

9.1.0.2 Exercise

Explain what valid and powerful mean in this sense. Can you give an example of a test that is always valid, but never powerful?

Click for the answer

Valid means not exceeding the type I error rate set. Powerful means having large power against alternatives we are interested in detecting. A test that is always valid but never powerful is e.g. a test that never rejects. Such a test has type I error and power 0. More subtly, it could be a test that tosses a coin and rejects with probability \(\alpha\), irrespective of the data. Such a test has type I error \(\alpha\) and power \(\alpha\), whatever the alternative.

\(~\)

9.1.0.3 Exercise

Calculate the power of the test with \(N=6\) for testing \(H_0: \sigma^2 = 1 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: \sigma^2 > 1\) with test statistic \(T= \max(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n) - \min(X_1,X_2,\dots,X_n)\), when the true value of \(\sigma^2\) is 2.

Click for the answer 
# from the previous exercise, we have the critical value
critical_value <- 4.02

# get power: simulate test statistics under the alternative
alt_statistics <- replicate( 1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, 0, sqrt(2))
  diff(range(X))
})
power <- mean(alt_statistics > critical_value)
power
## [1] 0.33793

\(~\)

9.1.0.4 Exercise

Now let’s use the sample variance as our test statistic instead of the range to testing \(H_0: \sigma^2 = 1 \quad \text{versus} \quad A: \sigma^2 > 1\). again, suppose the sample size is \(N=6\).

  1. Use simulation to calculate the critical value for the testing at significance level 5%

  2. Use simulation to calculate the power of the test, when the true value of \(\sigma^2\) is 2.

Click for the answer 
# a 
N <- 6
# get critical value: simulate test statistics under H0
null_statistics <- replicate( 1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, 0, 1)
  var(X)
})
critical_value <- quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
critical_value
##      95% 
## 2.228841
# b.
# get power: simulate test statistics under the alternative
alt_statistics <- replicate( 1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, 0, sqrt(2))
  var(X)
})
power <- mean(alt_statistics > critical_value)
power
## [1] 0.34971

\(~\)

To get a valid test, any test statistic will do. To get a very powerful test, some test statistics are better choices than others. In this particular example above, \(S^2\) and \(\hat\sigma^2\) are the best choices. It can be shown mathematically that for the same level of significance, the resulting tests have greater power than any of the other choices against any alternative.

So, some test statistics are simply better than others – they are better at summarizing the pertinent information into a single number. In this section we describe general methods for finding good test statistics. We will use the likelihood to find them.

9.2 Equivalent tests

Some tests look very different but they are actually the same. We call two test statistics \(S\) and \(T\) equivalent if the test of level \(\alpha\) that rejects for large values of \(S\) and the test that rejects for large values of \(T\) always give the same result: either both reject or both don’t reject.

\(~\)

9.2.0.1 Exercise

Suppose that for \(H_0: \sigma^2=1\) versus \(A: \sigma^2>1\) the test that rejects \(H_0\) when \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) as level \(\alpha\). Show that the test for \(H_0\) against \(A\) that rejects when \(S > \sqrt{k_\alpha}\) also has level \(\alpha\). Show that the two tests either both rejects or both don’t reject. Are \(S\) and \(S^2\) equivalent test statistics?

Click for the answer

If the test that rejects when \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) has level \(\alpha\), that means that under \(H_0\), \[\mathrm{P}(S^2 > k_\alpha) = \alpha.\] Since \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) if and only if \(S > \sqrt{k_\alpha}\), we also have \[\mathrm{P}(S > \sqrt{k_\alpha}) = \alpha.\] Since \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) if and only if \(S > \sqrt{k_\alpha}\), either both of the tests reject or both don’t reject. We conclude that \(S\) and \(S^2\) are equivalent.

\(~\)

9.2.0.2 Exercise

Show that for \(H_0: \sigma^2=1\) versus \(A: \sigma^2>1\), \(S^2\) and \(\hat\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \bar X)^2\) are equivalent test statistics.

Click for the answer

Let \(k_\alpha\) be the critical value for \(S^2\), so the test that rejects when \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) has level \(\alpha\), that means that under \(H_0\), \[\mathrm{P}(S^2 > k_\alpha) = \alpha.\] Since \[(n-1)S^2 = \sum_{i=1}^n (X_i - \bar X)^2 = n\hat\sigma^2,\] so \((n-1)S^2/n = \hat\sigma^2\). We have that \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) if and only if \((n-1)S^2 > (n-1)k_\alpha\) if and only if \((n-1)S^2/n > (n-1)k_\alpha/n\), so \(\hat\sigma^2 > (n-1)k_\alpha/n\). Therefore, under \(H_0\), \[\mathrm{P}\big(\hat\sigma^2 > (n-1)k_\alpha/n\big) = \alpha,\] so \((n-1)k_\alpha/n\) is the critical value of \(\hat\sigma^2\). Since \(S^2 > k_\alpha\) if and only if \(\hat\sigma^2 > (n-1)k_\alpha/n\), either both of the tests reject or both don’t reject. We conclude that \(S^2\) and \(\hat\sigma^2\) are equivalent.

\(~\)

In general, we have the following simple rule:

if \(f(x)\) is a strictly increasing function, then \(T\) and \(f(T)\) are equivalent test statistics.

Strictly increasing means that if \(a > b\), then always \(f(a) > f(b)\).

Tests based on equivalent test statistics are essentially different ways of writing the same test: their formulas may look different, but their outcomes are always the same.

\(~\)

9.2.0.3 Exercise

Apply the rule to the previous two exercises. What is the function \(f\) in these cases?

Click for the answer

When comparing \(S\) and \(S^2\), we can take \(f(x)=\sqrt{x}\). This is strictly increasing, and \(S = f(S^2)\).

When comparing \(S^2\) and \(\hat\sigma^2\), we can take \(f(x) = (n-1)x/n\). This is strictly increasing, and \(\hat\sigma^2 = f(S^2)\).

\(~\)

When defining hypothesis tests, we always assumed that tests would reject for large values of the test statistic \(T\). However, there are also two-sided tests (e.g. the \(t\)-test) that reject not only when \(T > a\) but also when \(T < -a\). To avoid having to make specific theory on two-sided tests, we remark that the test that rejects when \(T > a\) or \(T < -a\) is the same as the test that rejects when \(T^2 > a^2\). This means we only need to think about one-sided tests. To make a two-sided test, we can simply square the test statistic and do a one-sided test on \(T^2\).

9.3 Test statistics motivated by likelihood

Finding a good test statistic means for a null hypothesis e.g. \(H_0: \theta=\theta_0\) means harnessing as much information as possible about the parameter \(\theta\) to show that it is different from 0. The information of the data on \(\theta\) is contained in the likelihood of \(\theta\). It makes sense to build a test statistic based on this likelihood.

There are three classical ways to make a test statistic based on the likelihood. These are summarized in a figure below. Almost every parametric test you have learned about is a special case of one of these!

  • The Wald test uses \[T_\mathrm{Wald}=\hat\theta -\theta_0.\]
  • The Likelihood Ratio test uses \[T_\mathrm{LRT}=\mathrm{loglik}(\hat\theta) - \mathrm{loglik}(\theta_0).\]
  • The Score test uses \[T_\mathrm{score} = \mathrm{loglik}'(\theta_0).\]

Figure: the three classical test statistics

Anytime we can calculate a likelihood, we can define Wald, Score and Likelihood Ratio tests. We can calculate them analytically or numerically.

\(~\)

9.3.0.1 Exercise

The likelihood ratio statistic is never negative. Why?

Click for the answer

Since \(\hat\theta\) is the MLE, its likelihood is higher than that of any other \(\theta\), so it cannot be less than the likelihood of \(\theta_0\).

\(~\)

9.3.0.2 Exercise

For the Wald, likelihood ratio and score tests statistics, what values do you expect to see if

  1. \(\theta = \theta_0\);
  2. \(\theta \gg \theta_0\)
  3. \(\theta \ll \theta_0\).

Here \(\ll\) and \(\gg\) mean “much smaller than” and “much greater than”.

Click for the answer

Wald: (1.) around 0; (2.) \(\gg 0\); (3.) \(\ll 0\).

Likelihood ratio: (1.) around 0; (2.) \(\gg 0\); (3.) \(\gg 0\).

Score: (1.) around 0; (2.) \(\gg 0\); (3.) \(\ll 0\).

\(~\)

9.3.0.3 Exercise

For the exponential distribution likelihood, calculate the Wald, likelihood ratio and score test statistics for \(H_0: \lambda=1\) analytically. You can use the expressions for the likelihood, score and MLE that we derived in previous exercises (see Day 5). Evaluate the test statistic if we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\).

Click for the answer

We write \(\lambda_0=1\) (since we have \(H_0: \lambda=1\)).

For the Wald test we use that the MLE is \(\hat\lambda = 1/\bar X\): \[T_\mathrm{Wald}=\hat\lambda -\lambda_0 \\ = 1/\bar X - 1.\]

For the likelihood ratio test, we use that the exponential likelihood is \[\mathrm{loglik}(\lambda) = n\log(\lambda) - \lambda \sum_{i=1}^n x_i\\ = n\log(\lambda) - n\lambda\bar X.\] We get

\[T_\mathrm{LRT}=\mathrm{loglik}(\hat\lambda) - \mathrm{loglik}(\lambda_0)\\ = n\log(\hat\lambda) - n\hat\lambda\bar X - n\log(\lambda_0) + n\lambda_0\bar X \\ = n\log(1/\bar X) - n(1/\bar X)\bar X - n\log(1) + n\bar X \\ = -n\log(\bar X) - n + n\bar X.\]

For the score test we use that \[\mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = \frac{n}{\lambda} - \sum_{i=1}^n x_i \\ = n/\lambda - n\bar X.\] We get \[T_\mathrm{score} = \mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda_0) \\ = n/\lambda_0 - n\bar X \\ = n - n\bar X.\]

X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
N = length(X)
T_Wald = (1-mean(X))/mean(X)
T_Wald
## [1] -0.6685083
T_LRT = -N * log(mean(X)) - N + N*mean(X)
T_LRT
## [1] 10.95017
T_score = N - N*mean(X)
T_score
## [1] -24.2

\(~\)

9.3.0.4 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown \(\lambda\). Calculate the Wald, likelihood ratio and score test statistics for \(H_0: \lambda=1\) numerically. Use that the MLE \(\hat\lambda\) is \(1/\bar X\).

Click for the answer 
X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
hat_lambda <- 1/mean(X)
lambda0 <- 1

# Wald
T_Wald = hat_lambda- lambda0
T_Wald
## [1] -0.6685083
# LRT
loglik_fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate = lambda, log=TRUE))
T_LRT = loglik_fun(hat_lambda) - loglik_fun(lambda0)
T_LRT
## [1] 10.95017
# score
step=0.0001
lambda_grid <- lambda0 + c(-step/2, step/2)
loglik <- sapply(lambda_grid, loglik_fun)
T_score <- diff(loglik)/step
T_score
## [1] -24.2

\(~\)

9.3.0.5 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown \(\lambda\). Calculate the Wald, likelihood ratio and score test statistics for \(H_0: \lambda=1\) numerically. Calculate the MLE numerically too.

Click for the answer 
X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik_fun <- function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate = lambda, log=TRUE))

hat_lambda <- optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,2), maximum = TRUE)$maximum
lambda0 <- 1

# Wald
T_Wald = hat_lambda- lambda0
T_Wald
## [1] -0.6685046
# LRT
T_LRT = loglik_fun(hat_lambda) - loglik_fun(lambda0)
T_LRT
## [1] 10.95017
# score
step=0.0001
lambda_grid <- lambda0 + c(-step/2, step/2)
loglik <- sapply(lambda_grid, loglik_fun)
T_score <- diff(loglik)/step
T_score
## [1] -24.2

\(~\)

As we see from the example, numerical calculation is often easier, especially if the formula for the likelihood is complex. Still, the formula version is useful because it can be further analyzed.

\(~\)

9.3.0.6 Exercise

Write the analytically derived Wald and and score tests each as \(f(\hat\mu) = f(1/\bar X)\) for some function \(f\). Are these functions \(f\) strictly increasing? What do you conclude?

Click for the answer

Call \(x = 1/\bar X\). Then

\(T_\mathrm{Wald}= 1/\bar X - 1 = x-1,\) so \(T_\mathrm{Wald} = f(1/\bar X)\) with \(f(x) = x-1\). Since \(f\) is strictly increasing, \(T_\mathrm{Wald}\) is equivalent to \(\hat\mu\).

\(T_\mathrm{score} = n - n\bar X = n - n/x,\) so \(T_\mathrm{score} = f(1/\bar X)\) with \(f(x) = n-n/x\). Note that \(1/\bar X= x\) is always positive. If \(x>0\), \(1/x\) is strictly decreasing, so -1/x is strictly increasing, and so is \(f(x) = n-n/x\). We conclude that \(T_\mathrm{score}\) is equivalent to \(\hat\mu\).

Since \(T_\mathrm{Wald}\) and \(T_\mathrm{score}\) are both equivalent to \(\hat\mu\), they are equivalent to each other.

\(~\)

9.3.0.7 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Calculate the two-sided Wald test statistic for \(H_0:\lambda = 2\) against \(A: \lambda \neq 2\) analytically and find its critical value numerically. Do we reject \(H_0\)?

Click for the answer

We need to find the MLE analytically. We’ve done this before, but let’s do it again. The Poisson density is \(f(x) = e^{-\lambda} \lambda^x/x!\), so the log density is \(\log f(x) = -\lambda + x\log(\lambda) - \log(x!)\). The log likelihood is therefore \[ \mathrm{loglik}(\lambda) = \sum_{i=1}^n \{-\lambda + x_i\log(\lambda) - \log(x_i!)\} \\ = -n\lambda + \log(\lambda) \sum_{i=1}^n x_i - \sum_{i=1}^n \log(x_i!).\] Differentiating, we obtain \[ \mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = -n + \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] We now solve \[-n + \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i = 0 \\ \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i = n \\ \sum_{i=1}^n x_i = \lambda n \\ n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i = \lambda.\] so the MLE is \(\hat\lambda = \bar X\). Since our null hypothesis is \(H_0: \lambda =2\), we have \(T_\mathrm{Wald} = \hat\lambda-\lambda_0 = \bar X - 2\).

X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda0 = 2
observed_statistic = abs(mean(X) - lambda0)
observed_statistic
## [1] 0.1
null_statistics = replicate(1e5, {
  X = rpois(N, lambda=lambda0)
  abs(mean(X) - lambda0)
})
hist(null_statistics, 100)

critical_value = quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
critical_value
## 95% 
## 0.9

Since the observed test statistic does not exceed the critical value, we do not reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

9.3.0.8 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Calculate the two-sided Wald test statistic for \(H_0:\lambda = 2\) against \(A: \lambda \neq 2\) numerically and find its critical value numerically. Do we reject \(H_0\)?

Click for the answer 
X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda0 = 2
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))

MLE = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,4), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
observed_statistic = (MLE - lambda0)^2 #squared because two-sided
observed_statistic
## [1] 0.00999994
null_statistics = replicate(1e5, {
  X = rpois(N, lambda=lambda0)
  loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
  MLE = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,4), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
  (MLE - lambda0)^2
})
hist(null_statistics, 100)

critical_value = quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
critical_value
##      95% 
## 0.809984

Since the observed test statistic does not exceed the critical value, we do not reject \(H_0\).

Alternatively, we could have used the not-squared version

observed_statistic = MLE - lambda0 
observed_statistic
## [1] 0.0999997
null_statistics = replicate(1e5, {
  X = rpois(N, lambda=lambda0)
  loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
  MLE = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,4), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
  abs(MLE - lambda0)
})
hist(null_statistics, 100)

critical_value = quantile(null_statistics, 0.975)
critical_value
##    97.5% 
## 1.000003

But then we should check whether the test statistic is greater than the critical value or smaller than minus the critical value.

\(~\)

9.3.0.9 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X=(-1.2, 1.8, -0.5, 0.4, 3.4, 3.6)\) from a normal model with with known \(\mu=1\) and unknown \(\sigma^2\). Test \(H_0:\sigma^2=1\) against \(A:\sigma^2 \neq 1\) numerically using a likelihood ratio test.

Click for the answer 
X = c(-1.2,  1.8, -0.5,  0.4,  3.4,  3.6)
N = length(X)
loglik_fun = function(sig2) sum(dnorm(X, mean=1, sd=sqrt(sig2), log=TRUE))
hat_sig2 = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0, 10), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
sig2_0 = 1
observed_statistic = loglik_fun(hat_sig2) - loglik_fun(sig2_0)
null_statistics = replicate(1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, mean=1, sd=sqrt(sig2_0))
  loglik_fun = function(sig2) sum(dnorm(X, mean=1, sd=sqrt(sig2), log=TRUE))
  hat_sig2 = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0, 10), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
  loglik_fun(hat_sig2) - loglik_fun(sig2_0)
})
critical_value = quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
observed_statistic
## [1] 3.602949
critical_value
##      95% 
## 2.023098

Since the observed statistic is greater than its critical value, we reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

9.4 What have we learned

  • We can calculate Wald, score and likelihood ratio test statistics both numerically and analytically
  • We can find critical values for these test statistic (and any others) by simulation
  • We can say whether or not two test statistics are equivalent

10 Asymptotic tests and confidence intervals

We saw that in the exponential distribution model the one-sided score and Wald tests are equivalent. It is often the case that they are similar to each other, and that their two-sided variants are similar tot the likelihood ratio test. We will now investigate the behavior of the three tests in large samples.

10.1 Large sample distributions

We will use the fact that, as \(N\) increases, well-behaved likelihoods start to look more and more like linkelihoods of \(\mu\) in a normal distribution. Let us investigate the Wald, Likelihood Ratio and Score tests for the case of testing \(H_0: \mu=0\) against \(A: \mu \neq 0\) with \(\sigma^2\) known. In the normal distribution likelihood, the Fisher information does not depend on \(\mu\), we we denote it simply by \(\mathcal{I}\). Remember that \(\mathcal{I} = n/\sigma^2\).

The Wald test is easy to calculate. It has test statistic

\[T_\mathrm{Wald}= \hat\mu-0=\hat\mu.\]

\(~\)

10.1.0.1 Exercise

Show that the Wald test statistic has a normal distribution with mean 0 and variance \(1/\mathcal{I}\).

Click for the answer

\(\hat\mu = n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i\) has mean 0 and variance \(\sigma^2/n\). The Fisher Information of \(\mu\) in the normal likelihood is \(n/\sigma^2\).

\(~\)

10.1.0.2 Exercise

Show that the Likelihood Ratio Test statistic for \(H_0: \mu=0\) is \(T_\mathrm{LRT}= \frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2\) and that the distribution of \(2T_\mathrm{LRT}\) is \(\chi^2_1\).

Click for the answer

We use the parabola formula we derived for the log likelihood of the normal distribution in Lecture 6.

\[ T_\mathrm{LRT} = \mathrm{loglik}(\hat\mu) - \mathrm{loglik}(0) \\ = \Big(-\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2 + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\hat\mu - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2}{2\sigma^2} - \frac n2 \log(2\pi\sigma^2)\Big) -\Big(-\frac{n}{2\sigma^2}\cdot 0^2 + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\cdot 0 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2}{2\sigma^2} - \frac n2 \log(2\pi\sigma^2)\Big) \\ = -\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2 + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\hat\mu \\ = -\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2 + \frac{n\hat\mu}{\sigma^2}\hat\mu \\ = \frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2\]

Since \(\hat\mu\) is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(\sigma^2/n\), \(\sqrt{\frac{n}{\sigma^2}} \hat\mu\) has a standard normal distribution. It follows that \[2 T_\mathrm{LRT} = 2\frac{n}{2\sigma^2} \hat\mu^2 = \Big( \sqrt{\frac{n}{\sigma^2}} \hat\mu \Big)^2\] is distributed like the square of a standard normal variable, which is a chi-square with 1 degree of freedom.

\(~\)

\(~\)

10.1.0.3 Exercise

Show that the Score Test statistic for \(H_0: \mu=0\) is \(T_\mathrm{score} = \frac{n}{\sigma^2} \hat\mu\), and that \(T_\mathrm{score}\) has a normal distribution with mean 0 and variance \(\mathcal{I}\).

Click for the answer

In Lecture 6 we found that the score for the likelihood of the normal distribution is \[\mathrm{loglik}'(\mu) = -\frac{n}{\sigma^2} \mu + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2}\]. We calculate

\[ T_\mathrm{score} = \mathrm{loglik}'(0) = -\frac{n}{\sigma^2} \cdot 0 + \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n x_i}{\sigma^2} \\ = \frac{n\hat\mu}{\sigma^2}\]

Since \(\hat\mu\) is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(\sigma^2/n\), we have that \(T_\mathrm{score}\) is normally distributed with mean 0 and \[ \mathrm{Var}(T_\mathrm{score}) = \Big(\frac{n}{\sigma^2}\Big)^2\mathrm{Var}(\hat\mu) = \Big(\frac{n}{\sigma^2}\Big)^2\frac{\sigma^2}{n} = \frac{n}{\sigma^2}.\]

\(~\)

The results that hold for the normal distribution likelihood hold for large samples in any well-behaved likelihood. We have the following asymptotic distributions for the three classical tests. In large samples, under \(H_0\),

  • The Wald test statistic is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(1/\mathcal{I}\).
  • Two times the likelihood ratio test is chi-squared distributed with 1 degree of freedom.
  • The score test statistic is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(\mathcal{I}\).

If we are not in the normal distribution case, generally \(\mathcal{I}\) depends on the parameter \(\theta\), which is known under \(H_0:\theta=\theta_0\). Since under \(H_0\) if \(N\) is large \(\hat\theta \approx \theta_0\), we may either use \(\mathcal{I}(\theta_0)\) or \(\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)\). It is conventional to use \(\mathcal{I}(\theta_0)\) for the score test and \(\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)\) for the Wald test.

The asymptotic distributions give us an easier way to calculate critical values of the three test statistics. We reject, e.g. using the Wald test one-sided if \[T_\mathrm{Wald} > z_{1-\alpha}/ \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)},\] where \(z_{1-\alpha}\) is the \(1-\alpha\)-quantile of the standard normal distribution.

\(~\)

10.1.0.4 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Calculate the two-sided Wald test statistic for \(H_0:\lambda = 2\) against \(A: \lambda \neq 2\) analytically and find its critical value asymptotically. Do we reject \(H_0\)?

Click for the answer

We already calculated the MLE as \(\hat\lambda = \bar X\).

To use the asymptotic distribution we must calculate the Fisher Information. It is not specified in the question whether we should do that analytically or numerically, so let’s try both ways.

Analytically, we found that \[ \mathrm{loglik}'(\lambda) = -n + \lambda^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i,\] so \[ \mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda) = - \lambda^{-2} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i.\] The Fisher Information is \[\mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(\lambda)] = \mathrm{E}[\lambda^{-2} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i] \\ = \lambda^{-2}n\lambda \\ = n/\lambda.\] In the MLE, this is \(n/\hat\lambda = n/\bar X\).

Numerically, we have

X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda0 = 2
hatlambda = mean(X)
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))

step = 0.001
lambda_grid = hatlambda + c(-step, 0, step)
loglik <- sapply(lambda_grid, loglik_fun)
score = diff(loglik)/step
FisherInfo_numeric = -diff(score)/step
FisherInfo_numeric
## [1] 4.761905
FisherInfo = N/hatlambda
FisherInfo
## [1] 4.761905
observed_statistic = hatlambda - lambda0
observed_statistic
## [1] 0.1
critical_value = qnorm(0.975) / sqrt(FisherInfo)
critical_value
## [1] 0.8981683

Since the observed test statistic does not exceed the critical value and is not less than minus the critical value, we do not reject \(H_0\).

In this case we see an excellent correspondence between the asymptotic results and the numerical ones. This is not always the case with such small \(N\).

\(~\)

A well-known example of a Wald test is the Binomial Test. Assuming a binomial distribution with known \(n\) and unknown \(p\), for testing \(H_0: p=p_0\) it uses \(\hat p - p_0\) as a test statistic, where \(\hat p = X/N\) is the MLE, and compares it to the asymptotic normal null distribution with variance equal to \(1/\cal I(\hat p) = \hat p (1-\hat p)/N\).

\(~\)

10.1.0.5 Exercise

Verify that the binomial test is the asymptotic Wald test for this model.

Click for the answer

To verify that the binomial test is the asymptotic Wald test, we only need to check that \(\hat p\) is indeed the MLE and that \(1/\mathcal I(\hat p) = \hat p (1-\hat p)/n\). Brace yourself for a long calculation.

The density is \[ f(x) = {x \choose N} p^x(1-p)^{(N-x)}.\] The log density is \[ log f(x) = \log {x \choose N} + \log(p) x + \log(1-p) (N-x),\] so this is also the log likelihood \[\textrm{loglik}(p) = \log {x \choose N} + \log(p) x + \log(1-p) (N-x).\] Differentiating with respect to \(p\), the first term drops out and we get the score \[\textrm{loglik}'(p) = X/p - (N-X)/(1-p).\] Solving, we get \[X/p - (N-X)/(1-p) = 0 \\ X/p = (N-X)/(1-p) \\ X(1-p) = p(N-X) \\ X-Xp = pN-Xp \\ X = pN \\ p = X/N,\] so \(\hat p = X/N\) is indeed the MLE.

For the Fisher Information, we differentiate again to get \[\textrm{loglik}''(p) = -X/p^2 - (N-X)/(1-p)^2.\] The Fisher information is therefore \[\mathcal{I}(p) = \mathrm{E}[-\textrm{loglik}''(p)] \\= \mathrm{E}[X/p^2 + (N-X)/(1-p)^2] \\= Np/p^2 + N(1-p)/(1-p)^2 \\= N/p + N/(1-p) \\= \frac{N(1-p)}{p(1-p)} + \frac{Np}{p(1-p)} \\= \frac{N}{p(1-p)}.\]

Indeed \(\mathcal I(\hat p) = \frac{N}{\hat p(1-\hat p)}\).

\(~\)

10.1.0.6 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X=(-1.2, 1.8, -0.5, 0.4, 3.4, 3.6)\) from a normal model with with known \(\mu=0\) and unknown \(\sigma^2\). Test \(H_0:\sigma^2=1\) against \(A:\sigma^2 \neq 1\) with a likelihood ratio test. Calculate the test statistic numerically but use the asymptotic critical value.

Click for the answer 
X = c(-1.2,  1.8, -0.5,  0.4,  3.4,  3.6)
N = length(X)
loglik_fun = function(sig2) sum(dnorm(X, mean=0, sd=sqrt(sig2), log=TRUE))
hat_sig2 = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0, 10), maximum=TRUE)$maximum
sig2_0 = 1
observed_statistic = loglik_fun(hat_sig2) - loglik_fun(sig2_0)
critical_value = qchisq(0.95, df=1)/2
observed_statistic
## [1] 7.015942
critical_value
## [1] 1.920729

Since the observed statistic is greater than its critical value, we reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

10.1.0.7 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X=(-1.2, 1.8, -0.5, 0.4, 3.4, 3.6)\) from a normal model with with known \(\mu=0\) and unknown \(\sigma^2\). Test \(H_0:\sigma^2=1\) against \(A:\sigma^2 > 1\) with a one-sided score test. Calculate the test statistic analytically and use the asymptotic critical value.

Click for the answer

The normal density with \(\mu=0\) is \[f(x) = \frac1{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}} e^{-\frac{x^2}{2\sigma^2}},\] so \[\log f(x) = -\frac12 \log(2\pi\sigma^2) - \frac{x^2}{2\sigma^2}.\] The log likelihood is therefore \[ \mathrm{loglik}(\sigma^2) = \sum_{i=1}^n \log f(x_i) \\= -\frac n2 \log(2\pi\sigma^2) - \frac{1}{2\sigma^2}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2.\] The score is \[ \mathrm{loglik}'(\sigma^2) = - \frac n{2\sigma^2} + \frac{1}{2\sigma^4}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2.\] We find

\[T_\mathrm{score} = \mathrm{loglik}'(1) = - \frac n{2} + \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2.\] The second derivative of the likelihood is \[ \mathrm{loglik}''(\sigma^2) = \frac n{2\sigma^4} - \frac{1}{\sigma^6}\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2,\] so the Fisher Information is \[\mathcal{I}(\sigma^2) = \mathrm{E}[-\mathrm{loglik}''(\sigma^2)] =\\ -\frac n{2\sigma^4} + \frac{1}{\sigma^6}\mathrm{E}[\sum_{i=1}^n x_i^2] \\= -\frac n{2\sigma^4} + \frac{n\sigma^2}{\sigma^6} \\= \frac n{2\sigma^4}. \] The variance of the score is \(\mathcal{I}(1) = n/2.\)

X=c(-1.2,  1.8, -0.5,  0.4,  3.4,  3.6)
N <- length(X)
score_statistic <- -N/2 + sum(X^2)/2
critical_value <- qnorm(0.95, mean=0, sd=sqrt(N/2))
score_statistic
## [1] 11.805
critical_value
## [1] 2.84897

Since the test statistic exceeds the critical value, we reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

10.1.0.8 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X=(-1.2, 1.8, -0.5, 0.4, 3.4, 3.6)\) from a normal model with with known \(\mu=0\) and unknown \(\sigma^2\). Test \(H_0:\sigma^2=1\) against \(A:\sigma^2 > 1\) with a one-sided score test. Calculate the test statistic numerically and use a numerically calculated critical value.

Click for the answer 
X=c(-1.2,  1.8, -0.5,  0.4,  3.4,  3.6)
N = length(X)
loglik_fun = function(sig2) sum(dnorm(X, mean=0, sd=sqrt(sig2), log=TRUE))
sig2_0 = 1
step=0.001
sig2_grid <- sig2_0 + c(-step/2, step/2)
observed_statistic <- diff(sapply(sig2_grid, loglik_fun))/step
null_statistics = replicate(1e5, {
  X <- rnorm(N, mean=0, sd=sqrt(sig2_0))
  loglik_fun = function(sig2) sum(dnorm(X, mean=0, sd=sqrt(sig2), log=TRUE))
  diff(sapply(sig2_grid, loglik_fun))/step
})
critical_value = quantile(null_statistics, 0.95)
observed_statistic
## [1] 11.805
critical_value
##      95% 
## 3.287895

Since the test statistic exceeds the critical value, we reject \(H_0\).

\(~\)

Finally, a note about the similarity of the three tests.

\(~\)

10.1.0.9 Exercise

Show that in the normal model likelihood \(T_\mathrm{Wald}\) and \(T_\mathrm{score}\) are equivalent, and that \(T_\mathrm{Wald}^2\), \(T_\mathrm{score}^2\) and \(T_\mathrm{LRT}\) are equivalent.

Click for the answer

Since \(T_\mathrm{Wald} = \frac{\sigma^2}{n} \hat\mu\) and \(T_\mathrm{score} = \frac{n}{\sigma^2} \hat\mu\), we can write \(T_\mathrm{Wald} = \frac{\sigma^2}{n} \hat\mu = \frac{\sigma^4}{n^2} \hat\mu f(T_\mathrm{score})\) with \(f(x) = \frac{\sigma^4}{n^2}x\). Since \(f(x)\) is strictly increasing, the two tests are equivalent.

The reasoning for the equivalence of \(T_\mathrm{Wald}^2\), \(T_\mathrm{score}^2\) and \(T_\mathrm{LRT}\) is completely analogous: \(T_\mathrm{Wald}^2 = K\hat\mu^2\), \(T_\mathrm{score}^2=L\hat\mu^2\) and \(T_\mathrm{LRT}= M\hat\mu^2\) for constants \(K\), \(L\), \(M\). A strictly increasing function \(f(x) = Kx/L\) therefore exists so that \(T_\mathrm{Wald}^2 = f(T_\mathrm{LRT})\) and the two are equivalent.

\(~\)

Again, what holds for the normal distribution, holds for every well-behaved model if \(N\) is large. This principle also applies to the equivalence of the Wald, Likelihood ratio and score tests: As \(N\) grows, if the likelihood is well-behaved, the difference between the results of two-sided Wald, likelihood ratio and two-sided score tests vanishes. We say

The two-sided Wald, likelihood ratio and two-sided score tests are asymptotically equivalent.

An overview of the Wald, score and likelihood ratio tests and their asymptotic distributions:

Statistic Definition Distribution
Wald \(\hat\theta - \theta_0\) \(\mathcal{N}\{0, 1/\cal I(\hat\theta)\}\)
Score \(\textrm{loglikelihood}'(\theta_0)\) \(\mathcal{N}\{0, \cal I(\theta_0)\}\)
Likelihood ratio \(\textrm{loglikelihood}(\hat\theta) - \textrm{loglikelihood}(\theta_0)\) \(\frac12 \chi^2_{\mathrm{df}=1}\)

10.2 Confidence intervals from Wald, likelihood ratio (and score) tests

We have discussed how the likelihood suggests useful test statistics: the Wald, likelihood ratio and score tests. We have also seen that hypothesis tests can be inverted to get confidence intervals. What do the confidence intervals of the Wald, likelihood ratio and score tests look like? This is what we will look at in the first half of this lecture.

In Lecture 8 we have learned that we can construct a confidence interval by inverting a hypothesis test. This means that we can find weird confidence intervals with weird hypothesis tests.

\(~\)

10.2.0.1 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution. Suppose we test \(H_0: \lambda=\lambda_0\) with a one-sided test that rejects for large values of \(\hat\lambda\) only. Use the asymptotic distribution to find the critical value. What does the resulting confidence interval look like? What is unusual about this interval?

Click for the answer

The test statistic \(\hat\lambda\) under \(H_0\) is asymptotically normal with mean \(\lambda_0\) and variance \(1/\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0) = n/\lambda_0^2\). This means that we reject \(H_0\) if \[\hat\lambda > \lambda_0 + z_{1-\alpha}\lambda_0/\sqrt{n} \approx \lambda_0 + z_{1-\alpha}\hat\lambda/\sqrt{n},\] so when \[\lambda_0 < \hat\lambda - \hat\lambda z_{1-\alpha}/\sqrt{n}.\] We don’t reject, therefore, when \[\lambda_0 > \hat\lambda -\hat\lambda z_{1-\alpha}/\sqrt{n}.\]

X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
N = length(X)
hat_lambda = 1/mean(X)
lower_bound = hat_lambda - hat_lambda * qnorm(0.95) / sqrt(N) 
upper_bound = Inf
c(lower_bound, upper_bound)
## [1] 0.1740901       Inf

This is a perfectly valid confidence interval, but it looks strange because it is one-sided. Perfectly valid in theory, one-sided intervals are seldom used in practice.

This interval has an extremely weak upper bound that includes all values of \(\lambda\) higher than \(\hat\lambda\). In compensation, it has a slightly sharper lower bound than the two-sided interval, using \(z_{1-\alpha}\) instead of \(z_{1-\alpha/2}\).

\(~\)

In Lecture 9 we have learned about Wald, likelihood ratio and score tests as good ways to construct hypothesis tests. What do the confidence intervals we construct from these tests look like?

We focus on the asymptotic distributions of these tests because they are easier to work with. Remember that for large samples, under \(H_0\),

  • The Wald test statistic is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(1/\mathcal{I}\).
  • Two times the likelihood ratio test is chi-squared distributed with 1 degree of freedom.
  • The score test statistic is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance \(\mathcal{I}\).

Inverting the score test often involves quite a bit of algebra even for relatively simple distributions, as we see in the next exercise. We will focus here on the Wald and likelihood ratio test based confidence intervals.

\(~\)

10.2.0.2 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown \(\lambda\). Formulate \(H_0: \lambda = \lambda_0\). Use a grid of values of \(\lambda_0\) to find where the two-sided score test does not reject. Use the asymptotic distribution of the score test statistic. Use that the score of the exponential distribution is \(n/\lambda - n\bar X\) and the Fisher information is \(n/\lambda^2\). What is the resulting confidence interval for \(\lambda\)?

Click for the answer 
X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
N <- length(X)
lambda0 <- seq(0.001,1, by=0.001)
score <- N/lambda0 - N* mean(X)
FisherInfo <- N/lambda0^2
critical_value <- qnorm(0.975) * sqrt(FisherInfo)
reject <- abs(score) > critical_value
c(min(lambda0[!reject]), max(lambda0[!reject]))
## [1] 0.144 0.519

\(~\)

10.2.0.3 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown \(\lambda\). Formulate \(H_0: \lambda = \lambda_0\). Find analytically for which values of \(\lambda_0\) the two-sided score test does not reject. Use the asymptotic distribution of the score test statistic. What is the resulting confidence interval for \(\lambda\)?

Click for the answer

The score test statistic we have calculated before as \[T_\mathrm{score} = n/\lambda_0 - n\bar X.\] The Fisher information in \(\lambda_0\) is \(\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0) = n/\lambda_0^2\). We can use the asymptotic approximation (although maybe we shouldn’t because \(n\) is quite small) that says that, under \(H_0\), \(T_\mathrm{score}\) is approximately normal with mean 0 and variance \(\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)\). The two-sided test rejects when either \[T_\mathrm{score} > z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)} \qquad \textrm{or} \qquad T_\mathrm{score} < -z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)}.\] It follows that it does not reject when \[T_\mathrm{score} \leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)} \qquad \textrm{and} \qquad T_\mathrm{score} \geq -z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)}.\]

Working out the left-hand side, we get \[T_\mathrm{score} \leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\mathcal{I}(\lambda_0)} \\ n/\lambda_0 - n\bar X \leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{n}/\lambda_0 \\ \frac{n-z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{n}}{\lambda_0} \leq n\bar X \\ \frac{n-z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{n}}{n \bar X} \leq \lambda_0 \\ \frac{1-z_{1-\alpha/2}/\sqrt{n}}{\bar X} \leq \lambda_0.\]

The right-hand side similarly gives \[\frac{1+z_{1-\alpha/2}/\sqrt{n}}{\bar X} \geq \lambda_0.\]

The score-based confidence interval is therefore from \[ \frac{1-z_{1-\alpha/2}/\sqrt{n}}{\bar X} \qquad \textrm{to} \qquad \frac{1+z_{1-\alpha/2}/\sqrt{n}}{\bar X}\] We calculate

X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
N = length(X)
lower_bound = (1 - qnorm(0.975)/sqrt(N))/mean(X)
upper_bound = (1 + qnorm(0.975)/sqrt(N))/mean(X)
c(lower_bound, upper_bound)
## [1] 0.1439361 0.5190474

\(~\)

10.2.0.4 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X = (1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown \(\lambda\). Formulate \(H_0: \lambda = \lambda_0\). For which values of \(\lambda_0\) does the two-sided Wald test not reject? Use the asymptotic distribution of the Wald test statistic. What is the resulting confidence interval for \(\lambda\)?

Click for the answer

The Wald test statistic we have calculated before as \[T_\mathrm{Wald} = 1/\bar X- \lambda_0.\] The Fisher information in \(\hat\lambda\) is \(\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda) = n/\hat\lambda^2 = n\bar X^2\). We can use the asymptotic approximation (although maybe we shouldn’t because \(n\) is quite small) that says that, under \(H_0\), \(T_\mathrm{Wald}\) is approximately normal with mean 0 and variance \(1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)\). The two-sided test rejects when either \[T_\mathrm{Wald} > z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)} \qquad \textrm{or} \qquad T_\mathrm{Wald} < -z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)}.\] It follows that it does not reject when \[T_\mathrm{Wald} \leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)} \qquad \textrm{and} \qquad T_\mathrm{Wald} \geq -z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)}.\]

Working out the left-hand side, we get \[T_\mathrm{Wald} \leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\lambda)} \\ 1/\bar X - \lambda_0 \leq z_{1-\alpha/2}/(\bar X\sqrt{n})\\ 1/\bar X - z_{1-\alpha/2} /(\bar X\sqrt{n}) \leq \lambda_0.\]

The right-hand side similarly gives \[1/\bar X + z_{1-\alpha/2}/ (\bar X \sqrt{n})\geq \lambda_0.\]

The Wald-based confidence interval is therefore from \[ 1/\bar X-z_{1-\alpha/2}/(\bar X \sqrt{n}) \qquad \textrm{to} \qquad 1/\bar X+z_{1-\alpha/2}/(\bar X \sqrt{n})\] We calculate

X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
N = length(X)
lower_bound = 1/mean(X) - qnorm(0.975)/(sqrt(N)*mean(X))
upper_bound = 1/mean(X) + qnorm(0.975)/(sqrt(N)*mean(X))
c(lower_bound, upper_bound)
## [1] 0.1439361 0.5190474

\(~\)

10.2.0.5 Exercise

Note that the Wald and score confidence intervals we have calculated are exactly the same. Why is that?

Click for the answer

In one of the exercises of Day 9 we found that for the exponential likelihood the Wald and score tests are equivalent. If tests are equivalent, they either both reject or both don’t reject. The values of \(\lambda_0\) for which they don’t reject are therefore the same, so the confidence intervals are the same.

\(~\)

10.3 Wald confidence intervals

Wald confidence intervals always have a simple form. The Wald test of \(H_0:\theta=\theta_0\), using its aymptotic distribution, does not reject when \[T_\mathrm{Wald} = \hat\theta-\theta_0\leq z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)} \qquad \textrm{and} \qquad T_\mathrm{Wald} = \hat\theta-\theta_0 \geq -z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)}.\] This is the same as not rejecting when \[\theta_0\geq \hat\theta - z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)} \qquad \textrm{and} \qquad \theta_0 \leq \hat\theta + z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)}.\]

The asymptotic Wald confidence interval is from \(\hat\theta - z_{1-\alpha/2}\sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)}\) to \(\hat\theta + z_{1-\alpha/2}\sqrt{1/\mathcal{I}(\hat\theta)}\).

\(~\)

10.3.0.1 Exercise

Find the asymptotic Wald confidence interval for a \(\lambda\) in a Poisson-distribution.

Click for the answer

We have previously calculated that the Poisson MLE is \(\hat\lambda = \bar X\), and the Poissin Fisher Information is \(\mathcal{I}(\lambda) = n/\lambda\). It follows that the Poisson confidence interval for \(\lambda\) goes from \[\hat\lambda - z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt(\hat\lambda/n) = \bar X - z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\bar X/n}\] to \(\bar X + z_{1-\alpha/2} \sqrt{\bar X/n}\).

\(~\)

10.3.0.2 Exercise

Calculate the coverage for the Wald confidence interval of the exponential distribution if the true \(\lambda=1/4\) and \(N=6\).

Click for the answer 
N = 6
lambda = 1/4
cover = replicate(1e5, {
  X = rexp(N, rate=lambda)
  lower_bound = 1/mean(X) - qnorm(0.975)/(sqrt(N)*mean(X))
  upper_bound = 1/mean(X) + qnorm(0.975)/(sqrt(N)*mean(X))
  (lower_bound <= lambda) & (upper_bound >= lambda)
})
mean(cover)
## [1] 0.95671

\(~\)

10.4 Likelihood confidence intervals

The confidence interval of the likelihood ratio test also has a relatively simple form. We fail to reject when \[T_\mathrm{LRT} = 2(\mathrm{loglik}(\hat\theta) - \mathrm{loglik}(\theta_0)) \leq \chi_{1-\alpha},\] which is when \[ \mathrm{loglik}(\theta_0) \geq \mathrm{loglik}(\hat\theta) -\chi_{1-\alpha}/2.\]

Since \(\chi_{1-\alpha}/2 \approx 1.92\), the likelihood ratio confidence interval for \(\theta\) consists of exactly those \(\theta\) for which the log likelihood ratio with the MLE is less than 1.92. Let’s visualize that:

critical_value = qchisq(0.95,df=1)/2
critical_value
## [1] 1.920729
X = c(1.0, 5.2, 2.1, 9.3, 0.7, 1.5, 2.5, 0.9, 1.0, 3.8, 6.6, 1.6)
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
lambda = seq(0, 1, by=0.001)
loglik = sapply(lambda, loglik_fun)
plot(lambda, loglik, type='l', ylim=c(-40,-25))
hat_lambda = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,6), maximum = TRUE)$maximum
abline(h=loglik_fun(hat_lambda)-critical_value, col='red')

We may find the boundaries of the confidence interval with uniroot.

f0 <- function(lambda) loglik_fun(lambda) - loglik_fun(hat_lambda) + critical_value
lower_bound = uniroot(f0, c(0.001, hat_lambda))$root
upper_bound = uniroot(f0, c(hat_lambda, 1))$root
c(lower_bound, upper_bound)
## [1] 0.1775346 0.5559667

The likelihood confidence interval consist of all values of \(\theta\) for which the log likelihood is no more than 1.92 below the log likelihood of the MLE.

10.4.0.1 Exercise

Let \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\) be observations from a Poisson distribution with parameter \(\lambda\). Find the likelihood confidence interval for \(\lambda\).
