10.5 What have we learned

  • We can use the asymptotic distribution of the Wald, score and likelihood ratio test statistics to find asymptotic critical values.
  • We know that the Wald, score and likelihood ratio test statistics are asymptotically equivalent.
  • We can calculate asymptotic Wald and likelihood confidence intervals.

11 The P-value

11.1 The level of significance

Recall the Belgian euro experiment where we wanted to test the null hypothesis \(H_0 : p=1/2\) versus the alternative \(H_0 : p \neq 1/2\). We can use an asymptotic Wald test, where we compute the z-value \[Z = \frac{X - np_0}{\sqrt{n p_0(1-p_0)}}\] where \(p_0=1/2\) is the value for the probability of heads under the \(H_0\). We compare \(Z\) to the standard normal distribution. We reject the null-hypothesis if we observe a large (positive or negative) value of \(Z\) because that would indicate a discrepancy between the observe proportion of heads and the hypothesized proportion of 1/2. In other words, we choose some “critical value” and reject the null-hypothesis if \(|Z|\) exceeds it.

To choose a suitable critical value, we must decide on an acceptable probability of a type I error. A type I error occurs when reject \(H_0\) when it is actually true. This is also called a “false positive” result.

The probability of a type I error is also called the “level of significance” of the test, and it is often denoted by \(\alpha\). If we choose \(\alpha=0.05\) then we must compare \(|Z|\) to the \(1-\alpha/2 = 97.5\)th percentile of the standard normal distribution, which is 1.96.

In the Belgian euro example, we observed 140 heads out of 250 tosses so

\[Z = \frac{X - np_0}{\sqrt{n p_0(1- p_0)}} = \frac{140 - 125}{\sqrt{67.5}}=1.9.\]

Because \(|Z|=1.9\) does not exceed the critical value 1.96, we do not reject the null hypothesis that the coin is fair at the level of significance \(\alpha=0.05\).

The level of significance is often chosen to be 0.05, but why? Let’s ask sir Ronald Fisher himself.

If one in twenty does not seem high enough odds, we may, if we prefer it, draw the line at one in fifty (the 2 per cent point), or one in a hundred (the 1 per cent point). Personally, the writer prefers to set a low standard of significance at the 5 per cent point, and ignore entirely all results which fail to reach this level.

\(~\)

11.1.0.1 Exercise

Do you think 0.05 is a good value for \(\alpha\)? Should it depend on the application field? Should each researcher be allowed to choose it themselves?

Click for the answer

The value of \(\alpha\) should depend on how acceptable it is to have false positive results (commit a type I error). This obviously depends on the field, and maybe even on the specific research question. Still, it is not a good idea if researchers can choose it themselves, since researchers have an incentive to choose it as large as possible.

\(~\)

The value of 0.05 is conventional, but arbitrary. We might also have chosen another value. To test at the \(\alpha=0.10\) level (two-sided), we must compare \(|Z|\) to the 95th percentile, which is 1.64.

qnorm(0.95)
## [1] 1.644854

Since the test statistic \(|Z| = 1.9\) is greater than 1.64, we do reject the null hypothesis at the \(\alpha=0.10\) level.

11.2 The marginal level of significance

In the Belgian euro example, we do not reject the null-hypothesis at level 0.05 but we do reject it at level 0.1. We can perform the test at many other levels of significance, and see at which levels we do or don’t reject. To do that, we must calculate the critical value at many levels (\(\alpha\)) and check if our test statistic \(|Z|=1.9\) exceeds them or not. We do this in the following script and show the result in a plot and a table.

x = 140
n = 250
p0 = 1/2
alpha = seq(0,1,0.005)
z = abs((x - n*p0)/sqrt(n*p0*(1-p0)))
critical_value = qnorm(1-alpha/2) 
plot(alpha, critical_value, type='l')
abline(h=z)
text(x=0.5, y = 2, labels="|Z|=1.9")

reject = z>critical_value
head(data.frame(alpha, z, critical_value, reject), 20)
##    alpha        z critical_value reject
## 1  0.000 1.897367            Inf  FALSE
## 2  0.005 1.897367       2.807034  FALSE
## 3  0.010 1.897367       2.575829  FALSE
## 4  0.015 1.897367       2.432379  FALSE
## 5  0.020 1.897367       2.326348  FALSE
## 6  0.025 1.897367       2.241403  FALSE
## 7  0.030 1.897367       2.170090  FALSE
## 8  0.035 1.897367       2.108358  FALSE
## 9  0.040 1.897367       2.053749  FALSE
## 10 0.045 1.897367       2.004654  FALSE
## 11 0.050 1.897367       1.959964  FALSE
## 12 0.055 1.897367       1.918876  FALSE
## 13 0.060 1.897367       1.880794   TRUE
## 14 0.065 1.897367       1.845258   TRUE
## 15 0.070 1.897367       1.811911   TRUE
## 16 0.075 1.897367       1.780464   TRUE
## 17 0.080 1.897367       1.750686   TRUE
## 18 0.085 1.897367       1.722384   TRUE
## 19 0.090 1.897367       1.695398   TRUE
## 20 0.095 1.897367       1.669593   TRUE

\(~\)

11.2.0.1 Exercise

In the plot and the table we see that there is an inverse (decreasing) relationship between the level of significance (\(\alpha\)) and the critical value. The smaller \(\alpha\), the larger the critical value. Explain why.

Click for the answer

Choosing \(\alpha\) to be small means that we want to ensure a small probability of a type I error. The only way to achieve this, is to set the critical value so high that there is a small probability of rejecting the null hypothesis.

So: Testing at a small level of significance is more strict than testing at higher level. That is, we need more evidence (in the form of a larger test statistic) to reject the null-hypothesis.

\(~\)

Since there is an decreasing relationship between the level of significance and the critical value, it follows that there is exactly one \(\alpha\) at which they are equal and the test decision changes. We call this value for \(\alpha\) the “marginal level of significance”, or the p-value.

The p-value is the smallest level of significance at which someone using a particular test statistic would reject the null hypothesis on the basis of the observed data.

From the plot and the table, we see that we do not reject when the level of significance is about 0.055 or less, but we do reject when the level of significance is about 0.055 or more. To compute the p-value exactly, we must find the value for \(\alpha\) where the critical value is equal to the observed z-value of 1.9. We can use the function uniroot:

margin = function(alpha) z - qnorm(1-alpha/2)   # = 1.9 - critical_value
uniroot(margin, c(0,1))$root                    # p-value
## [1] 0.05778042

\(~\)

11.2.0.2 Exercise

It follows directly from our definition that we reject the null hypothesis if and only if the p-value is smaller than the level of significance. Explain in your own words.

Click for the answer

The p-value is the smallest level of significance at which we would reject. So, at significance levels above the p-value we would reject, while below the p-value we wouldn’t.

\(~\)

The p-value is a measure of evidence against \(H_0\). Why? Because the smaller the \(\alpha\)-level, the more evidence against \(H_0\) we require before we are willing to reject \(H_0\). A small p-value, say 0.001, means that even if we would have taken a stringent approach to evidence with \(\alpha=0.005\), we would still have rejected \(H_0\). Note the “what-if” type of phrasing here! Of course, it makes no sense to choose the \(\alpha\)-level after seeing the \(p\)-value, so the \(p\)-value is not the type I error of the test.

\(~\)

The p-value is a number between zero and one, and a small p-value is evidence against the null hypothesis. This leads many people to believe that the p-value is the probability that \(H_0\) is true. This is absolutely not so! Finding a p-value of, say, 0.057 simply means that if you had set the level of significance at 0.057 (instead of 0.05) then your result would be (just) significant.

\(~\)

The p-value is also not the probability that the experimental result to “due to pure chance” or any other nonsense like that.

\(~\)

11.2.0.3 Exercise

Why is the p-value not the probability that \(H_0\) is true?

Click for the answer

It helps to consider what “the probability that the null hypothesis is true” actually means. To speak of this probability, we must be able to think of the truth of the null hypothesis as something random. This is not what we have done so far. \(H_0: \theta =\theta_0\) is a statement that either is true or false; it is not a random variable. In the frequentist framework we have introduced so far “the probability that the null hypothesis is true” is not defined. It can be defined, however, if you take the so-called Bayesian perspective. This will be discussed in the Bayesian statistics course.

\(~\)

Let’s compute the p-value in another example. Suppose we want to do a one-sided Wald test for \(H_0:\lambda=1\) versus the alternative \(H_1 : \lambda > 1\) in a Poisson model. We observe \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\). We can calculate the p-value as follows.

library(numDeriv)
X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda_0 = 1
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
hat_lambda = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,6), maximum = TRUE)$maximum  # compute the MLE (it's actually mean(X))
test_statistic = hat_lambda - lambda_0
Fisher_info=-hessian(loglik_fun,hat_lambda)   # compute the Fisher info (it's actually N/hat_lambda)
critical_value = function(alpha) qnorm(1-alpha, sd=1/sqrt(Fisher_info))
margin = function(alpha) test_statistic - critical_value(alpha)
uniroot(margin, c(0,1))$root    # p-value
## [1] 0.008191373

\(~\)

11.2.0.4 Exercise

Suppose we have observed \(X=(1.0,5.2,2.1,9.3,0.7,1.5,2.5,0.9,1.0,3.8,6.6,1.6)\) from an exponential distribution with unknown rate \(\lambda\). We want to do a two-sided Wald test of \(H_0 : \lambda=0.5\) versus the alternative \(H_1 : \lambda \neq 0.5\).

  1. Compute the MLE
  2. Compute the Fisher information.
  3. Compute the p-value.
Click for the answer 
X=c(1.0,5.2,2.1,9.3,0.7,1.5,2.5,0.9,1.0,3.8,6.6,1.6)
N=length(X)
lambda_0 = 0.5
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate=lambda, log=TRUE))
hat_lambda = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,2), maximum = TRUE)$maximum  # compute the MLE (it's actually 1/mean(X))
test_statistic = abs(hat_lambda - lambda_0)
Fisher_info=-hessian(loglik_fun,hat_lambda)   # compute the Fisher info (it's actually N/hat_lambda^2)
critical_value = function(alpha) qnorm(1-alpha/2, sd=1/sqrt(Fisher_info))
margin = function(alpha) test_statistic - critical_value(alpha)
uniroot(margin, c(0,1))$root
## [1] 0.07826178

\(~\)

11.3 The p-value as a tail probability

Using uniroot is not the most efficient way to compute the p-value. It is better to compute it as follows (revisiting the Poisson example above):

X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda_0 = 1
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
hat_lambda = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,6), maximum = TRUE)$maximum  # compute the MLE (it's actually mean(X))
test_statistic = hat_lambda - lambda_0
Fisher_info=-hessian(loglik_fun,hat_lambda)    # compute the Fisher info (it's actually N/hat_lambda)

# instead of uniroot, now use this:
1 - pnorm(test_statistic, sd=1/sqrt(Fisher_info))
## [1] 0.008188686

Why can we compute the p-value in this way? Recall that the p-value is the marginal significance level. In other words, it is the significance level at which the decision reject/don’t reject changes. But this happens precisely when the test statistic is equal to the critical value. We have used uniroot to find the value for \(\alpha\) where this happens.

Now, the p-value is defined as the level of significance of a test whose critical value happens to be equal to the observed test statistic. This particular significance level is the probability, under the null hypothesis, that the test statistic exceeds the observed value. In the code above, we simply computed this probability directly.

In terms of mathematics, we have the following. Suppose that under the null-hypothesis a test statistic \(T\) has cumulative distribution function \(F\). Then the p-value is given by \(p=1-F(T)\). (Don’t confuse this \(p\) with the probability of a success in de Belgian euro experiment!)

In light of this computation, the p-value is sometimes described as: the probability that the test statistic exceeds its observed value, if the null hypothesis is true. This description is very helpful when you want to compute a p-value, but it is not helpful at all when you want to understand what it is. It’s actually quite misleading. To interpret the p-value, you should simply think of it as the “marginal level of significance”.

\(~\)

11.3.0.1 Exercise

Calculate the p-value of the Belgian euro experiment again, but now using pnorm instead of uniroot.

Click for the answer 
x = 140
n = 250
p0 = 1/2
alpha = seq(0,1,0.005)
z = (x - n*p0)/sqrt(n*p0*(1-p0))
test_statistic=abs(z)         # observed value of the test statistic (|z|=1.9)
pnorm(-test_statistic) + 1 - pnorm(test_statistic)     # p-value = P(|Z|>1.9)
## [1] 0.05777957

Alternatively,

2*pnorm(-test_statistic)
## [1] 0.05777957

\(~\)

11.3.0.2 Exercise

Suppose we want to do a two-sided likelihood ratio test for \(H_0:\lambda=1\) versus the alternative \(H_1 : \lambda \neq 1\) in a Poisson model. Use the asymptotic distribution of the likelihood ratio statistic. We observe \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\). Use both uniroot and the direct calculation to get the p-value, and verify that they give (approximately) the same result.

Click for the answer

In this case, two times the log likelihood ratio has the chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom (asympotically) under the null hypothesis.

X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
lambda_0 = 1
loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
hat_lambda = optimize(loglik_fun, c(0,6), maximum = TRUE)$maximum
test_statistic = 2*(loglik_fun(hat_lambda) - loglik_fun(lambda_0))  # 2 x log likelihood ratio
critical_value = function(alpha) qchisq(1-alpha, df=1)
margin = function(alpha) test_statistic - critical_value(alpha)
uniroot(margin, c(0,1))$root
## [1] 0.00248791
1 - pchisq(test_statistic, df=1)
## [1] 0.002471777

\(~\)

We will now revisit a few exercises from day 8.

11.3.0.3 Exercise

Suppose that 160 patients are divided randomly into two groups of 80. The patients in the first group are given some treatment, and 30 of the 80 recover from their illness. In the other group, the patients are given a placebo, and only 20 recover. So, we have the following 2x2 table

Observed = matrix(c(30,50,20,60),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Observed
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   30   50
## [2,]   20   60

We can use the chi-squared test for the null-hypothesis that there is no difference between the treatment and placebo. Compute the p-value by calculating the appropriate tail probability.

Click for the answer

Under the null hypothesis (no difference) we estimate the probability of recovery at p=50/160. So, the 2x2 table of expected counts is

p=50/160
Expected = matrix(c(80*p,80*(1-p),80*p,80*(1-p)),nrow=2,byrow=TRUE)
Expected
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   25   55
## [2,]   25   55

The chi-squared statistic is

X2=sum((Observed - Expected)^2/Expected)
X2
## [1] 2.909091

Under the null-hypothesis, X2 has the chi-squared ditribution with 1 degree of freedom. So, the p-value is

1-pchisq(X2,1)
## [1] 0.08808151
We do not reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

\(~\)

11.3.0.4 Exercise

Suppose a supermarket sells potatoes in 1 kilo bags. We buy 7 bags and weigh them. We find 983, 1041, 1026, 1025, 1033, 968 and 1028 (grams). We know that the standard deviation of the weight is 25 grams. We want to test \[H_0 : \mu = 1000 \quad \text{versus}\quad A : \mu \neq 1000\] Compute the p-value by calculating the appropriate tail probability.

Click for the answer

The Z statistic is

x=c(983,1041,1026,1025,1033,968,1028)
z=sqrt(7)*(mean(x)-1000)/25            # n=7, sd=25
z
## [1] 1.572332

Under the null hypothesis, z has the standard normal distribution. So, the p-value is

2*pnorm(-abs(z))
## [1] 0.1158735
We do not reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

z
## [1] 1.572332

Under the null hypothesis, z has the standard normal distribution. Now we reject only when \(z\) is too small. So, the p-value is

pnorm(z)
## [1] 0.9420632
We do not reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

11.4 Monte-Carlo computation of the p-value

So far we have used the asymptotic distribution. We can also calculate exact p-values numerically. If we simulated test statistics from the distribution under the null hypothesis, the p-value is the probability mass of the null distribution that is more extreme than the observed statistic, which is simply the number of simulated test statistics that exceed the observed value.

We demonstrate this approach by calculating the p-value for the Belgian euro example using the simulated null distribution of the absolute difference between the number of heads and 125.

Since we don’t have to worry about the theoretical distribution of the test statistic under \(H_0\), we might as well use the intuitive \(|X-125|\).

X = 140
N = 250
p_0 = 1/2
test_statistic=abs(X-125)
X=rbinom(10^5,size=N,p=p_0)   # sampling under the null hypothesis
null_statistics=abs(X-125)
mean(null_statistics >= test_statistic)  # p-value
## [1] 0.06683

As always, note how simple this is! We only need to be able to sample data under the null hypothesis. It does not matter how simple or complicated the test statistic is.

Compare this result to the p-value of 0.057 which we got by using the normal approximation of the binomial distribution. In this very simple example we can also compute the p-value exactly:

X = 140
N = 250
p_0 = 1/2
pbinom(110,size=N,p=p_0) + 1 - pbinom(139,size=N,p=p_0)
## [1] 0.06642115

\(~\)

11.4.0.1 Exercise

Why 139 and not 140?

Click for the answer

If we use \(|X-125|\) as our test statistic, then the two-sided p-value is \(P(|X-125| \geq 140)\). We have \[ \begin{align*} P(|X-125| \geq 140) &= P(X \leq 110) + P(X\geq 140)\\ &= P(X \leq 110) + 1 - P(X < 140) \\ & = P(X \leq 110) + 1 - P(X \leq 139) \end{align*}\]

\(~\)

11.4.0.2 Exercise

Suppose we want to do a two-sided Wald test for \(H_0:\lambda=1\) versus the alternative \(H_1 : \lambda \neq 1\) in a Poisson model. Use the simulated distribution of the test statistic. To avoid repeatedly using the optimize function, you can use that the MLE of \(\lambda\) is just the average \(\bar X\). Suppose we observe \(X = (0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)\).

Click for the answer 
X = c(0, 3, 3, 4, 2, 0, 1, 4, 0, 4)
N = length(X)
lambda_0 = 1
hat_lambda = mean(X)                        # MLE
test_statistic = abs(hat_lambda - lambda_0) # Wald statistic
null_statistics = replicate( 1e5, {
  X = rpois(N, lambda=lambda_0)    # sampling under the null hypothesis
  abs(mean(X) - lambda_0)
})
mean(null_statistics >= test_statistic)  # p-value
## [1] 0.00168

\(~\)

11.4.0.3 Exercise

Now calculate the p-value of the likelihood ratio test for the Poisson problem using the simulated null distribution of the likelihood ratio statistic.

Click for the answer

  loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dpois(X, lambda=lambda, log=TRUE))
  hat_lambda = mean(X)

})

## [1] 0.00384

Suppose we have a sample of size \(n = 5\) from the normal distribution with mean \(\mu = 0\) and unknown standard deviation \(\sigma\). 11.4.0.5 Exercise

Suppose we have a random sample of size \(n\) = 12 and want to test the (null) hypothesis that they were drawn from the normal distribution with mean 1 and standard deviation 1 versus the alternative that they were drawn from the exponential distribution with mean 1. We know that the normal distribution is symmetric, so that the (population) mean and de median are equal. The exponential distribution, however, is skewed to the right so that the mean is larger than the median. So, we decide to use the following test: Compute the sample mean \(\bar x\) and the sample median \(m\), and reject the null hypothesis if \(T=\bar x - m\) is large. Suppose we observe \(T=0.5\).

  1. Use simulation to determine the p-value.
  2. Make a histogram of the simulated test statistics and compare to the observed \(T=0.5\)
Click for the answer 
test_statistic = 0.5
null_statistics = replicate( 1e5, {
  X = rnorm(12, mean=1, sd=1)   # sampling under the null hypothesis
  mean(X) - median(X)
})
mean(null_statistics >= test_statistic)  # p-value
## [1] 0.00432

So, the difference between the sample mean and the sample median is larger than we would expect if the data were sampled from a normal distribution with mean and standard deviation one.

hist(null_statistics,100)
abline(v=0.5,col="red")

\(~\)

11.5 The sampling distribution of the p-value

The p-value is a function of the data, and therefore a random variable. What is the distribution of the p-value under the null hypothesis? Let’s try a Wald test in an exponential model and look at the distribution under \(H_0\).

lambda0 = 1/4
N = 100
p_values = replicate( 1e5, {
  X = rexp(N, rate=lambda0)
  hat_lambda = 1/mean(X)
  T_Wald = hat_lambda - lambda0
  FisherInfo = N/hat_lambda^2
  2*pnorm(-abs(T_Wald), mean=0, sd=sqrt(1/FisherInfo))
})
hist(p_values)

We recognize the (standard) uniform distribution. This holds in general; the null distribution of a p-value is uniform. We can see that analytically as follows. If the test statistic has cumulative distribution function (CDF) \(F\), then \(p=1-F(T)\) is the p-value. We can now derive the CDF of the p-value \(p\) and then we find that it is the CDF of the standard uniform distribution. For \(0 \leq x \leq 1\), we have

\[ \begin{align*} \mathrm{P}(p \leq x) &= \mathrm{P}(1-F(T) \leq x)\\ &= \mathrm{P}(F(T) \geq 1-x) \\ &= \mathrm{P}(T \geq F^{-1}(1-x)) \\ &= 1-\mathrm{P}(T \leq F^{-1}(1-x))\\ &=1-F(F^{-1}(1-x)) \\ &= 1-(1-x)= x. \end{align*} \]

This is indeed the cumulative distribution function of the standard uniform distribution.

Since \(p=1-F(T)\) is simply a transformation of the test statistic \(T\), we can also view the p-value as a test statistic. Of course, if we use the p-value as a test statistic, we must reject for small values, rather than large ones.

The attractiveness of using the p-value as a test statistic, lies in the fact that is has such a simple null distribution and therefore such a simple critical value, namely \(\alpha\) itself.

A p-value is a transformed test statistic for \(H_0\) that has a uniform (0,1) distribution under \(H_0\).

The uniform distribution is only approximate if we use the asymptotic distribution of the test statistic, or if the test statistic is discrete.

\(~\)

11.5.0.1 Exercise

Make histograms of the null distribution of the p-values for the asymptotic likelihood ratio test of \(H_0: \lambda = 1/4\) in a an exponential model with \(N=3\) and \(N=40\).

Click for the answer 
lambda_0 = 1/4
N = 3
p_values = replicate( 1e5, {
  X = rexp(N, rate=lambda0)
  hat_lambda = 1/mean(X)
  loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate = lambda, log=TRUE))
  test_statistic = 2*(loglik_fun(hat_lambda) - loglik_fun(lambda_0))
  1 - pchisq(test_statistic, df=1)
})
hist(p_values,100)

lambda_0 = 1/4
N = 40
p_values = replicate( 1e5, {
  X = rexp(N, rate=lambda0)
  hat_lambda = 1/mean(X)
  loglik_fun = function(lambda) sum(dexp(X, rate = lambda, log=TRUE))
  test_statistic = 2*(loglik_fun(hat_lambda) - loglik_fun(lambda_0))
  1 - pchisq(test_statistic, df=1)
})
hist(p_values,100)

The distribution is noticeably closer to uniform when the sample size is larger. This is especially clear at lower p-values and that is also where it is more relevant.

\(~\)

11.6 Criticism of the p-value

First of all, there is nothing wrong with the p-value in and of itself. The math is all correct and it does what it is supposed to do. Still there is much discussion about the and improper use of the p-value (or rather, hypothesis testing in general). American Statistical Association, confusingly, issued a statement in 2016 to warn against the over-interpretation of statistical significance, followed in 2021 by another statement endorsing the p-value.

The criticism roughly concerns the following four points.

  1. Interpretation As we discussed, the interpretation of p-values is quite subtle. Users tend to misinterpret the p-value as the probability that the null hypothesis is true, or the probability that the data are random, or such things. See Steven Goodman’s dirty dozen or Sander Greenland’s guide to misinterpretation for nice discussions.

  2. The replication crisis A statistical hypothesis test at level \(\alpha\) is set up in such a way that the probability of a type I error (reject the null hypothesis when it is actually true) does not exceed \(\alpha\). That’s the math and it is entirely correct. Unfortunately, the reality is that statistical tests are vulnerable to cheating. For example, one can easily get \(p<0.05\) by manipulating the data in various ways (leaving out “outliers”, transforming variables or other forms of pre-processing), trying out many different models and tests (“p-hacking”), or testing many hypotheses and only reporting the significant ones (“fishing”). The results of such “analyses” will typically not replicate in the sense that if other researchers try to repeat the experiment they will not find similar results. Much has been written about this replication crisis in science. Justifiably or not, the p-value is often blamed for this mess, see for example this article in Nature in which the authors “call for the entire concept of statistical significance to be abandoned.”

  3. Dichotomous thinking A “dichotomy” is a division or contrast between two things that are or are represented as being opposed or entirely different. Statistical tests in general, and p-values in particular, are said to encourage dichotomous thinking. Users will think that \(p<0.05\) implies that the null-hypothesis is false and that \(p>0.05\) means it is true. In fact, the distinction is not that clear-cut because the difference between “significant” and “not significant” is not itself statistically significant. For example, Consider two independent studies with effect estimates and standard errors of 25 \(\pm\) 10 and 10 \(\pm\) 10. The first study is statistically significant at the 1% level, and the second is not at all statistically significant, being only one standard error away from zero. Thus, it would be tempting to conclude that there is a large difference between the two studies. In fact, however, the difference is not even close to being statistically significant: the estimated difference is 15, with a standard error of \(\sqrt{10^2 + 10^2}=14\).

  4. The file drawer The idea that results that are not statistically significant are not useful and not worthy of publication has distorted the scientific literature. Below is a histogram of more than one million z-values (converted from p-values) from the Medline archive. As we know, z-values between -2 and 2 are not significant at the 5% level. Clearly, they are largely missing from the published record. They ended up collecting dust in the researcher’s proverbial “file drawer”. As a result, the scientific literature appears much more successful than it actually is.

Note that, though there are many critics of the p-value, almost no two critics agree on an alternative, since most alternatives share some of the drawbacks of the p-value, or introduce novel drawbacks of their own. The discussion continues!

Recall what sir Ronald Fisher said:

If one in twenty does not seem high enough odds, we may, if we prefer it, draw the line at one in fifty (the 2 per cent point), or one in a hundred (the 1 per cent point). Personally, the writer prefers to set a low standard of significance at the 5 per cent point, and ignore entirely all results which fail to reach this level.

These words have had quite an impact over the last century!

11.7 What have we learned

  • We can explain the p-value as a marginal significance level.
  • We can calculate p-values as a tail probability.
  • We know the null distribution of a p-value.
  • We can interpret a p-value as a test statistic.
